<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--AirportDeer     12-24 0118</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Airport Deer,0122</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Takeoff Aborted After Deer Seen on Runway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines crew had to postpone
their takeoff when a group of eight deer strolled across the runway.
There was no sign of a sleigh or a jolly man in a red suit,
witnesses said.
   The crew of another plane noticed the deer Friday and radioed
Kansas City International Airport's control tower, which notified
the Northwest pilots, said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman
Bob Raynesford.
   Raynesford said no passengers were injured during the aborted
takeoff, which he called ``an unusual event but really rather
routine.''
   The flight, which was headed to Minneapolis-St. Paul Airport, got
off a few minutes later, he said.
</TEXT>
