<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RobinsonMemorial     12-24 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robinson Memorial,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Robinson Tried To ``Change the Temperature''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former ABC News anchorman Max Robinson, who
died of complications resulting from AIDS, was eulogized by the Rev.
Jesse Jackson as a man who ``wouldn't adjust, wouldn't knuckle under
the face of ... racism.''
   Jackson, a close friend of Robinson's, delivered the eulogy
Friday at a Washington church where friends and co-workers of the
nation's first black network television anchor paid their last
respects.
   Robinson, said Jackson, ``wouldn't adjust, wouldn't knuckle under
the face of obvious and not so obvious racism.''
   Robinson had been ill for more than a year when he died Tuesday
at Howard University Hospital at age 49.
   ``Max Robinson never adjusted,'' Jackson said. ``He sought to
transform. He was not a TV thermometer who measured things and
spilled them back out. He tried to be a thermostat _ to change the
temperature.''
   Jackson told reporters that he talked to Robinson about how he
had contracted AIDS and that Robinson told him: ``It is not
homosexuality but it was promiscuity. ... Let my predicament be a
source of education to our people.''
   Among those attending the ceremony were ABC News President Roone
Arledge, ABC anchorman Peter Jennings, CBS anchorman Dan Rather, 60
Minutes reporter Ed Bradley and CNN anchorman Bernard Shaw.
   ``I think ABC News is a better place today than it was before Max
was there,'' said Arledge. ``A lot of that is due to his efforts.''
   Robinson began his broadcasting career as a radio station disc
jockey in his hometown of Richmond, Va. He moved to Washington in
1965 and three years later became the first black to anchor
newscasts at a major TV station, appearing on the 6 p.m. and 11 p.m.
news on Channel 9 WTOP, now WUSA, with co-anchor Gordon Peterson.
   Robinson then left Washington after 10 years at the top of the
ratings to join ABC as the first black to anchor a network news
show. He was one of three anchors at ABC, along with Jennings and
Frank Reynolds.
   The frustrated Robinson made headlines publicly denouncing racism
at the news organization during a speech at Smith College in
February 1981.
   Arledge was supervising news coverage when Robinson was an
anchor, and he changed ABC News' three-anchor format after Reynolds
died in 1983. At that point, Jennings inherited the job as sole
anchor of the newscasts, and Robinson was assigned to do news briefs
and weekend anchor.
   In 1984, he left ABC News in Washington and joined WMAQ-TV in
Chicago. The following June, he entered a hospital specializing in
alcohol rehabilitation suffering from emotional and physical
exhaustion, according to Nick Aronson, director of communications at
WMAQ-TV. Aronson said Robinson never returned to the station, and
did sporadic freelance work after that.
   He is survived by his mother, Doris Robinson Griffin, and
stepfather, the Rev. James Griffin, both from Norfolk, Va., and four
children, Mark, Maureen, Michael and Malik Robinson.
   Robinson also leaves three surviving siblings, Jewel R. Shepperd,
Jean Robinson Yancey and civil rights activist Randall Robinson, the
head of TransAfrica. All live in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
