<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-24 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drivers who overstayed their parking meters
received a surprise holiday message _ in meter _ from Montgomery
County.
   Parking employees in the county north of Washington, D.C., put a
few lines of poetry on the windshields of violators Thursday instead
of the usual $10 tickets. The 4-by-8 inch cards bore this greeting:
   ``The meter was red as time had expired
   ``In the rush of the season we knew you'd be tired,
   ``A parking ticket would just make you blue
   ``In the holiday spirit this just wouldn't do,
   ``So during this time of friendship and good cheer
   ``Season's Greetings to you and best wishes all year.''
   The holiday gesture cost the county approximately $10,000 in
potential fines, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TEMPLE CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 56 years, Betty Sedat and Grace
Dutton have been exchanging Christmas cards _ or rather one
Christmas card, sent back and forth year after year.
   The greeting features a bagpipe-playing Scotsman with the verse:
``Hoot! for a Jolly Christmas! I'll send a card to wish ye a
Christmas full of cheer. I'll send my name in pencil so ye'll use
the card next year.''
   Mrs. Sedat first sent the card to her friend in 1932.
   ``I thought it was funny,'' she said. ``So I did sign it in
pencil along with the date, mailed it off to Grace, and forgot all
about it.''
   Sure enough, a year later it returned with Ms. Dutton's name
signed below Mrs. Sedat's.
   ``We signed and dated it every year, in pencil of course, first
on the front, then on the back, until we ran out of room,'' Mrs.
Sedat said.
   The exchange continued even after Mrs. Sedat moved to Guatemala
with her husband to do missionary work for several years with the
Nazarene Church.
   The friends say their relationship has been as durable as the
card.
   ``We keep in touch, and see each other several times a year,''
said Mrs. Sedat.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For those who aren't resolving to tighten their
budgets for the new year, a Boston hotel is offering ``total
indulgence'' for ``as long as you want it or can afford it'' _ at a
mere $3,000 per night.
   Beginning Jan. 3, the Boston Ritz-Carlton will join with the new
$2 million Spa at The Heritage a block away to offer guests a night
of ``unparalleled, unremitted pampering,'' according to the hotel's
promotional literature.
   The $3,000-per-couple package _ tax and tips included _ offers
limousine pick-up, a night in the posh hotel's Presidential Suite,
unlimited food and drink and ``all the spa services that two people
can indulge in individually or collectively.''
   Spa guests may attend an exercise class, use the health club's
weightlifting and cardiovascular equipment, or swim in a four-lane
pool that features ``artistic falling leaves across the bottom in
colorful tiles.''
   Next is an hour of massage _ Swedish, polarity, cross fiber,
sports or shiatsu _ or a choice of herbal steam wraps, Austrian mud
body treatment, seaweed body wrap, cellulite treatment, clay body
wrap, brush and tone treatment, or a Swiss shower.
   The package also includes a detailed fitness evaluation and
nutrition advice, a facial, blow-dry and, for women, make-up
consultation and application.
   In addition to its classic French cuisine, the hotel also offers
low-calorie, low-cholesterol and low-sodium dishes.
