<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OilSpill 1stLd-Wriththru a0697 12-24 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld - Wriththru, a0697,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Spills In Pacific After Tug Hits Barge</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with size of slice increases to 30 miles;
at least 50 birds found with oil on feathers; oil seen on beach,
other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WESTPORT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fuel oil from a leaking barge began
washing ashore on resort beaches of the southwestern Washington
coast Friday, and at least 50 birds were found with oil on their
feathers, officials said.
   The barge trailed an oil slick that grew to 30 miles long and 100
feet wide in the hours after a Thursday night collision with a
tugboat, Coast Guard officials said.
   Authorities closed 1{ to 2 miles of beach in the Ocean Shores
area near here, on the north side of Grays Harbor, where oiled birds
were found. The area contains numerous wetlands and marshes that are
home to migratory waterfowl.
   Rescue teams were being mobilized to try and clean and save as
many birds as possible, authorities said.
   ``The latest reports I'm getting indicate an average of 12 dead
or distressed birds are being found every quarter of a mile along
the beach,'' said Mark Stewart, a spokesman for the state Divison of
Emergency Management.
   The leaking barge was towed south to the mouth of the Columbia
River, which separates Oregon and Washington. It bobbed 25 miles
offshore Friday night while authorities waited for daylight to
assess how best to repair it.
   Washington state officials estimated some 70,000 gallons of oil
had spilled from the barge, said Bob Steelquist of the Washington
state Department of Wildlife.
   The oil was leaking from a tank holding about 250,000 gallons of
oil, said Coast Guard Lt. Eldo DeLong in Seattle. In all, the barge
held about 2.75 million gallons of oil, but only the one tank was
leaking.
   Sause Bros. Ocean Towing Inc., of Coos Bay, Ore., operators of
the barge and its tugboat, hired crews to clean up the beaches.
   The accident occurred Thursday night as a tow line either broke
or was being adjusted in heavy seas between the tug Ocean Services
and the barge, named the Nestucca. The accident occurred about two
miles off Grays Harbor, on the southwestern Washington coast.
   The barge had been scheduled to make a delivery at Grays Harbor,
then head to Portland, said Dick Lauer of Sause Bros.
   Officials said they would have a better idea Saturday of the
extent of the damage to beaches and wildlife.
   Grays Harbor County Sheriff Dennis Morrisette said he could smell
oil in the air and the sand was darker than usual.
</TEXT>
