<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Rodney Dangerfield is suing a hotel
chain he claims didn't give him any respect when it hired an actor
to impersonate his voice in radio commercials.
   The commercials for Park Inns International of Irving, Texas,
carried a disclaimer that said the voice was an impersonation of
Dangerfield.
   But the comedian's lawsuit contends the disclaimer wasn't clear
because it was followed by the actor saying Dangerfield-style, ``You
mean this guy ain't a real announcer? He really had me fooled.''
   The advertising campaign was launched in the summer without
permission from Dangerfield or his agent, according to the suit
filed recently in U.S. District Court.
   Daryl Robertson, an attorney for the chain, was unavailable for
comment late Friday. There was no response to a message left with
the hotel's management company, Emerson Management of Dallas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Rooney and Ann Miller will have their run of
``Sugar Babies'' cut short in January because the musical is losing
money, a spokeswoman for London's Savoy Theater said.
   The Broadway hit opened in London on Sept. 20 and had been
expected to run at least six months, but the cast has been told the
curtain will come down Jan. 7.
   ``The last couple of weeks, audiences have only been about 40
percent. They spent a lot of money advertising the show, but it had
almost no effect,'' the spokeswoman said Friday. ``There is no sign
of things getting any better, so the only thing to do was to close
it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STATELINE, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby says his efforts to modernize
his mother's kitchen with Christmas presents were for nought _ she
insisted on treating the gifts as trophies.
   ``I tried to give her presents I really thought she needed _ an
electric toaster, a waffle iron, a percolator coffee pot; She loved
them all,'' the comedian said. ``But did she use them? No.
   ``She put them all on top of the refrigerator like they were
trophies from the Olympics and she'd get really mad if anyone took
them down and tried to use them.''
   Cosby, who is to appear at a hotel-casino Jan. 3-8, said he
particularly remembers looking up at a shiny new toaster while
browning bread the hard way.
   ``For years, we still made our toast in the bottom of the oven,''
he recalled recently. ``You put it in, wait a while, then turn it
over and burn your fingers while that terrific stainless steel
toaster ... sat on top of the refrigerator.
   ``My mother was a little strange about Christmas.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Esai Morales is giving up his holiday
feasting for a three-day fast to protest the use of pesticides by
California grape growers.
   Morales, who starred in the 1987 hit movie ``La Bamba,'' accepted
a crucifix made of dried grape vines from union leader Cesar Chavez
at a ceremony Friday.
   The cross was worn by Chavez, president of United Farm Workers
Union, during his 36-day fast that ended Aug. 21. It has been passed
on since then to politicians and celebrities including the Rev.
Jesse Jackson and Martin Sheen.
   The union claims the pesticides have caused cancer in farm worker
families.
   Morales plans to fast through Christmas Day.
