<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Minnesota Vikings quarterback Joe
Kapp is recuperating from a broken collarbone after being struck by
a taxi while jogging with his dog.
   Kapp, 50, was crossing a street in nearby Los Gatos on Thursday
when a car driven by Festus Banjo, 46, turned a corner and hit Kapp
with its right front bumper, police said.
   Kapp was knocked unconscious and was taken to Valley Medical
Center in San Jose. The dog wasn't hurt.
   ``We're fine,'' Kapp said from his hospital bed Thursday night.
``It was a rainy morning; I didn't see the car at all. I was lucky.
It could have been worse. The last I heard, the car wasn't hurt too
badly.''
   Los Gatos police said Banjo would be cited for violating a
pedestrian's right-of-way.
   Kapp led the Vikings to the Super Bowl in 1970 and later coached
the University of California-Berkeley football team for five years.
