<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MotherMurder 2ndLd-Writethru a0716 12-24 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mother Murder, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0716,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second-Degree Murder Verdict Set Aside in `Baby Blues' Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CORRECT that judge did issue finding of
not guilty by reason of insanity, adds detail on unusual nature of
ruling, judge's comment after hearing. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `Mrs.
Massip...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second-degree murder conviction of a
woman who claimed the ``baby blues'' caused her to run over her
infant son with a car was set aside Friday by a judge who found the
woman innocent by reason of insanity.
   Sheryl Massip, 24, who testified that post-partum depression
drove her to kill the colicky, constantly crying boy, was not guilty
of murder, said Superior Court Judge Robert R. Fitzgerald.
   ``I do not believe the prosecution's evidence established that
she had the requisite mental state of malice aforethought,'' the
judge said. He said while he knew his ruling was unusual, he felt he
had no choice.
   Unless overturned on appeal by the prosecution, the judge's
ruling invalidates a Nov. 17 jury verdict of second-degree murder,
which called for a sentence of 15 years to life.
   Fitzgerald delivered what he referred to as an ``unprecedented''
decision: first reducing the charge against her from second-degree
murder to voluntary manslaughter, then ruling that she was not
guilty by reason of insanity. The decision, however, still leaves
the defendant eligible for commitment to a mental hospital for up to
11 years.
   ``This is new ground that we plowed today,'' the judge said in an
interview with the Los Angeles Times after issuing his ruling. ``I
don't know of another court that came to a decision like the one I
ded to set aside the jury verdict altogether.
   ``I know people will say I've overstepped my bounds. But the more
I thought about it, the more I realized I didn't have any choice but
to find her insane. ... She was bonkers.''
   Mrs. Massip welcomed the verdict.
   ``I was praying the people would understand,'' she said outside
court. ``The jury did not understand, but I'm thankful that the
judge did.''
   Mrs. Massip testified at the trial that on April 29, 1987, her
own 23rd birthday, she hit her 6-week-old son, Michael, on the head
with a garden tool, then put him under the wheels of the family
station wagon, ran over him and put his body in a trash can.
   Defense witnesses said an exceptionally bad case of post-partum
depression, a hormonal ailment known as the ``baby blues,'' was to
blame. Defense attorney Milton Grimes said the young mother was
wracked by lack of sleep and hallucinations and that she heard
voices telling her to put the boy out of his misery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881224-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Honduras-Nicaragua     12-24 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras-Nicaragua,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Threatens To Take Nicaragua Before Int'l Court of Justice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoya said
Honduras may file a countersuit against Nicaragua before the U.N.
International Court of Justice.
   His accusation that Nicaragua's Sandinista army has intruded into
Honduran territory, killing soldiers and civilians, came after the
court announced Tuesday it will rule on a complaint filed by
Nicaragua against Honduras on July 28, 1986.
   Azcona said his country is ready to defend itself against
Nicaragua's accusation that Honduras has aided the U.S.-backed
troops, known as the Contras, by allowing them to use Honduran
territory as a staging ground for a war against the Sandinista
government.
   Azcona Hoyo told reporters the decision by the court in The Hague
did not surprise him.
   But, he added, ``We have enough proof that the Sandinista army
has entered Honduran territory. ... We have documented proof of
numerous armed attacks and that have resulted in the death of
Honduran soldiers and civilians.''
   Azcona Hoya said the Contras have taken refuge in Honduras
because they were driven there by the Sandinista army. He said they
are not fighting in Nicaragua now.
   Azcona Hoyo said he considered the Contras to be political
refugees and predicted U.S. aid for them would be renewed in 1989,
after George Bush is inaugurated president.
</TEXT>
