<DOCNO> AP881224-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CajunChristmas Bjt   12-24 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cajun Christmas, Bjt,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heaux, Heaux Heaux: Levee Bonfires Lead Papa Noel to Cajun
Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Down here, where folks wish you a ``Joyeux
Noel'' instead of ``Merry Christmas,'' Santa's sleigh gives way to
Papa Noel's Cajun canoe and people build bonfires to light his way
on Christmas Eve.
   ``I don't know how that sleigh would run down here. If it needs
snow he'd be in trouble. I guess that's why he comes down the river
in a pirogue'' _ a flat-bottomed canoe, said Nolan J. Oubre, the
police and fire chief of Gramercy.
   Gramercy has a population of 3,600, except for Christmas Eve when
upwards of 40,000 people crowd into town for the lighting of the
bonfires along the Mississippi River levee, Oubre said.
   For 260-plus years the bonfires have blazed to guide Papa Noel
down the Mississippi to the small south Louisiana communities about
30 miles north of New Orleans.
   ``The bonfires are an old tradition passed on from my grandfather
and his grandfather and all the other grandfathers, I guess,'' said
the 65-year-old Oubre, who has been in charge of building the
bonfires for 50 years.
   People began building the structures they'll torch on Christmas
Eve almost a month in advance.
   ``They used to be just simple teepees but about eight years ago
people started getting real imaginative in what they made. Now it's
amazing to see what they come up with,'' Oubre said.
   About 100 bonfires a year in the shape of riverboats, plantation
homes, cabins and Viking ships spring up on the river banks along a
three-mile stretch.
   In fact, the builders' imaginations soared to such heights that
size restrictions were imposed. Bonfires can be no larger than
12-feet wide and no taller than 25 feet.
   ``Those are about the only restrictions,'' Oubre said.
   The crowds attracted by the celebration bring traffic that backs
up for miles along State 44, but Oubre said he doesn't consider it a
problem.
   ``It may be a problem for the folks in the cars, but not for us.
They can only go about three or four miles an hour so it's not
dangerous and they can watch the bonfires just fine,'' he reasoned.
   Not everyone will be stacked up in traffic. At least six river
boats will carry thousands of people upriver from New Orleans to
watch.
   ``This is the second year we've done it, and we sold out before
we even advertised or planned it this year. We added a third boat,
the River Rose, and still have better than 200 people on a waiting
list,'' said Anna Catherine Viator, spokeswoman for New Orleans
Paddlewheels Inc.
   For between $35 and $55, those on the various ships get dinner,
champagne, jazz and about an eight-hour trip, cruise officials said.
   Oubre and his 12-man crew worked almost three weeks to build a
38-foot-long pyre that looks like a shrimp boat. They cut willow
trees, which he said burn best and make a ``beautiful fire,'' and
carefully assembled them.
   Oubre said watching his creations go up in smoke each year isn't
sad in spite of the work and time that go into them.
   ``No, that's why you build them,'' he said. ``You've got it in
mind all the time to see them burn so you look forward to that part
most of all.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
