<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Of Commons Gives Canada-U.S. Trade Agreement Final Approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canada-U.S. free trade agreement won final
approval early Saturday by a vote of 141-111 in the House of Commons.
   It was the final reading for the trade agreement's enabling
legislation, and the new pact is scheduled to take effect New Year's
Day after approval by the Senate.
   The Senate, which is to complete its work next week, has promised
not to oppose the trade legislation.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, whose Progessive Conservative
Party won a second consecutive majority government in Nov. 21
elections, signed the trade agreement with President Reagan in
January. The opposition had bitterly opposed the pact, claiming it
would cost Canadians jobs.
   The agreement is to phase out all remaining tariffs between the
two neighbors over a 10-year period.
   A smiling Mulroney said early Saturday that the deal will bring
economic prosperity.
   ``People will look back on this and say it was a good day for
Canada.''
</TEXT>
