<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Homeless-Cash     12-24 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Homeless-Cash,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dead Homeless Man Carried $5,200 In Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 63-year-old homeless man was found dead on a
city sidewalk with $5,200 in cash on him, police said.
   The victim was identified Thursday as Timothy Simmons, based on
fingerprints taken when he was arrested for vagrancy in 1949, said
homicide Detective Paul Marraway. Simmons had no known address in
Pittsburgh.
   Simmons was found Monday in a cubbyhole outside a boiler plant in
a housing complex. He was covered by several blankets, and his feet
were bare.
   Police originally suspected Simmons froze to death, but an
autopsy showed he died of natural causes, said Allegheny County
Deputy Coroner Floyd Coles.
   Officers searched Simmons on the sidewalk and said they found a
wad of bills worth $1,250 in his pocket. The coroner's staff later
found a packet containing $4,000 strapped to his thigh.
   Simmons apparently saved the money from his wages as a laborer
unloading food trucks in the city's produce section, known as the
Strip District.
   The coroner's office is trying to locate Simmons' relatives, who
would inherit the money, Coles said.
</TEXT>
