<1ST_LINE>u i PM-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru   12-24 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0436,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaragua-Honduras Bickering Puts Peace Talks In Jeopardy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf, `Honduran Foreign...' to restore dropped word
in quote. Inserts 2 grafs after 18th, `In both...' to add rebel
attack. Pickup 19th pvs, `The regional...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bickering between Nicaragua and
Honduras is threatening a summit planned for next month by Central
American leaders anxious to end the civil wars and hostilities in
the region.
   The latest stumbling block comes from the International Court of
Justice at The Hague, Netherlands. The World Court agreed this week
to hear Nicaragua's claims that Honduras has been harboring and
supporting U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, who are fighting
Nicaragua's leftist government.
   Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said Wednesday
the World Court's decision threatens the future of negotiated
settlements to the region's problems. He said the court's move is
politically charged and sets ``a judicial precedent totally
incompatible with peace negotiations.''
   In addition, President Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras has
threatened to boycott regional peace talks unless Nicaragua drops
its World Court case.
   Lopez and the foreign ministers of Nicaragua, El Salvador,
Guatemala, and Costa Rica met earlier this month in Mexico. There
they agreed that heads of state would convene in January in an
effort to breathe new life into the stalled August 1987 peace plan.
   The plan sets three-month deadlines for cease-fires in El
Salvador, Nicaragua and Guatemala.
   It also mandates that governments of all five nations enact
political amnesties and democratic freedoms and reconcile with
political opposition groups. It calls for an end to outside aid for
rebel insurgencies and a ban on the use of one country's territory
to destabilize another.
   The peace proposal was written by President Oscar Arias of Costa
Rica, who was awarded the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize for his effort.
   Honduras says anti-government Nicaraguan rebels and refugees camp
exist on Honduran territory because of a lack of democratic freedoms
in Nicaragua.
   ``For reasons of national security, Honduras doesn't want the
Contras,'' Lopez said. ``Nor do we desire the presence of more than
60,000 refugees from Guatemala, El Salvador and Nicaragua.''
   However, Lopez said Honduras cannot eject the Contras because,
``We would be accused of being responsible for massacres and
violating human rights.''
   Lopez denounced what he called the Sandinista practice of using
international organizations to pressure other nations.
   But Nicaragua hailed the court's decision, and Nicaraguan
President Daniel Ortega said Honduras should accept it.
   The same court ruled in Nicaragua's favor in 1986 in a suit
against U.S. support of the Contras. The United States has refused
to recognize the court's jurisdiction in the area.
   As the main judicial organ of the United Nations, the court has
no enforcement powers.
   The Arias plan sought to end the Honduran problem as well as long
wars in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala. But the heady days
following the 1987 signing later turned to disappointment and
frustration.
   The four U.S. allies in Central America _ El Salvador, Honduras,
Costa Rica and Guatemala _ blame Nicaragua and its largest backer,
the Soviet Union, for the persistent turmoil. Nicaragua says the
United States is trying to militarize the region and find a pretext
to invade Nicaragua.
   In both El Salvador and Guatemala, talks between leftist
guerrillas and the two U.S.-backed governments have fallen apart.
Wars rage on with no end in sight.
   In San Salvador on Friday, leftist rebels attacked the Defense
Ministry with car bombs and explosives, killing at least three
people and wounding at least 35, officials said.
   The assault on the military headquarters compound and on a nearby
government health clinic appeared to be part of a major rebel
offensive.
   The regional talks did lead to a cease-fire agreement in
Nicaragua last March that sharply curtailed fighting there. A month
earlier, the U.S. government cut off military aid to the Contras.
   About 10,000 Contra fighters have now moved back to base camps in
Honduras. The presidents last met in Costa Rica on Jan. 15, the date
set by the Arias plan to mark the end of the wars and full democracy.
   Instead, they signed a statement vowing to continue their
efforts. El Salvador's President Jose Napoleon Duarte, whose
government is fighting growing rebel activity, said further meetings
would be useless unless concrete progress could be made.
</TEXT>
