<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TankerExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru a0440 12-24 0733</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Explosion, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0440,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Explodes Into Huge Fireball, Kills Seven</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with complete death toll now at
eight, including traffic death; picks up 7th graf, ``Authorities
issued ...;'' INSERTS 1 graf after penultimate graf, ``Authorities
tentatively ...,'' with detail.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MX2,4; LaserGraphic NY38</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10,000-gallon propane truck exploded
Friday on a highway, killing seven people, sparking a huge fireball
and sending the tanker crashing into a house 125 yards away,
officials said.
   Six people were admitted to hospitals, including one who later
died and another in critical condition, and five others were treated
and released. A traffic jam caused by the crash led to an accident
that claimed a eighth life.
   ``I heard the explosion and saw the tanker flying through the
air. It fell on the house and just blew up,'' said Marvin Mitchell,
a witness.
   The wood-frame, duplex house was destroyed and a 10-year-old girl
inside died, authorities said. An elderly woman also inside the
house died later of her burns.
   The six other deaths, including the driver of the truck, and most
of the injuries occurred mainly on Interstate 240 near downtown as
the fireball engulfed the truck and several other vehicles, said
fire Capt. Benny McDow.
   The people taken to hospitals suffered mostly from burns, McDow
said. One was listed in critical condition early Saturday in the
burn unit of the Regional Medical Center and four other people were
also hospitalized. O
   Authorities issued tentative identifications, but said dental
records would have to be used for positive identification, because
some of the bodies were so badly burned.
   The propane truck apparently skidded off an exit ramp on
Interstate 240 as the driver tried to turn onto Interstate 40 toward
Arkansas, McDow said. The roadway was dry.
   ``He was trying to exit and lost control and hit a retaining
wall,'' McDow said. ``That exit there is short. It's one of those
tight turns.''
   Jed Tennison, who works at a sheet metal plant near the crash
scene, said he rushed to a highway overpass when he heard the
explosion.
   ``There was a guy on fire rolling on the road and there was
another just lying on the ground where somebody must have put him,''
Tennison said.
   Gaines Tennison, Jed's father and manager of the sheet metal
plant, said he felt the shock of the blast and looked out to see
what had happened.
   ``I thought it was an earthquake,'' he said. ``The whole sky was
white, just lit up. You could feel the heat inside the building.''
   Frank Baker, a deputy chief in charge of fire department crews on
the scene, said victims killed by the blast had little chance to
escape the flames.
   ``There was a huge fireball, maybe 700 to 800 feet. It engulfed
three or four cars,'' Baker said.
   In addition to the destroyed duplex, the fireball damaged five
houses, three on one side and two on the other side of the six-lane
highway, authorities said.
   James Edgeston, who lives two doors away from the destroyed
duplex, said a truck axle with four wheels attached ended up in his
kitchen. He suffered a cut on the head but was not seriously hurt.
   John Stonecipher, a city fire marshal, said the tanker ruptured
on one end and blasted off like a rocket when the fuel ignited. ``It
was like an unguided missile,'' he said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board planned to send a team
of investigators, said Michael Benson, NTSB spokesman in Washington.
   Authorities tentatively identified the victims as Shelanda
Towles, 10, killed in her house; Randall Benson, 29, West Memphis,
Ark., the propane tanker driver; and four people who were in
vehicles near the exploding truck: Harrison G. Lee, 34, Brighton,
Tenn.; Robert Wardlow, 40, Memphis; and Tina Wiles, 30, and her
father-in-law, Warner Wiles, 70, both of Vicksburg, Miss.
   The elderly woman who was inside the duplex with Shelanda was not
identified because her family had not been notified, said police
traffic Lt. James Krepela.
   After the accident, traffic backed up for several miles north and
south of town. A second truck driver was killed when his 18-wheeler
plowed into the rear of a car tied up in the traffic jam, police
said. That driver was identified as David Bailey, 29, of West
Helena, Ark.
</TEXT>
