<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesperateAddict Bjt   12-24 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Desperate Addict, Bjt,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Addict Won't Be Home for Christmas _ And He's Glad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack addict desperate for treatment brought
police his paraphernalia, then smashed windows at two precincts
before a judge relented and sentenced him to a drug program he calls
his ``best Christmas gift yet.''
   ``I will thank him for giving me an opportunity for starting my
life back over. He is an understanding man, one of very few,''
Alexis Vega said Friday of Bronx Criminal Court Judge John Moore.
   Vega, 34, said his life had bordered on the insane until Moore
sentenced him to 90 days in a drug treatment program. As a crack
cocaine addict, Vega lost his job as a construction worker. He
stopped paying bills. He became irresponsible and dirty. His wife of
two years, Josephine Coulter, feared for their 11-month-old son and
her two daughters, now 12 and 13.
   Last July, Miss Coulter threw him out of their home in New York
City's tough South Bronx section ``because I was doing wrong,'' he
said. ``She is a Christian and I didn't want to be around her.''
   ``It's bad to see a good husband turn into a monster. I've known
him nine years and I had never seen that side of him,'' Miss Coulter
said. ``I was praying he would get into a program before it was too
late. He was getting out of hand.''
   Vega knew he was getting out of hand, so he turned for help. He
applied for admission at several Bronx hospital programs and one in
Manhattan.
   ``They all told me they were filled up. Until February or the end
of January. That was too far for me to look forward to,'' Vega said.
   On Oct. 28, he sought help from the desk sergeant at the 47th
Precinct. That did not work, so Vega tried something else: He placed
a syringe and some crack vials on the sergeant's desk.
   ``I didn't know what else to do,'' Vega said. ``They roughed me
up. They were very shocked that I did this. They didn't understand.''
   And neither did the judge who handled the case, releasing him two
days later without sending him to treatment.
   On Nov. 5, Vega tossed a chair through the window of the 48th
Precinct. Another judge put him in the streets without treatment.
   On Nov. 14, he threw a padlock through a window of the 46th
Precinct. He was processed by a third judge who did not offer
treatment.
   ``I told them I needed help,'' Vega said.
   All the pending cases of drug charges and criminal mischief came
together Dec. 1 before Moore, who decided to do something.
   ``I got a call from the judge on Tuesday the 20th. From the judge
himself,'' said Luis Sierra, a worker at and graduate of Way Out
Church Ministries Inc.
   ``It was strange. To me, a judge has a lot to do. He went out of
his way to help this particular person. The probation report was not
favorable.''
   Sierra said the program, which is funded by donations and other
churches, has 58 beds and 600 people on the waiting list. One bed
was available and Vega got it. Vega, who had previously written to
the program, was given a 90-day sentence Wednesday to Way Out.
   ``He's got a long way to go here,'' Sierra said. ``It is a strain
on his life. We are a very strict program.''
   ``Strict'' means no leaving the program for two months, no
visitors, no cursing, no smoking and plenty of prayer.
   The Bronx District Attorney, Paul Gentile, commended the judge
and said ``this case dramatizes the critical need for treatment upon
demand for all individuals addicted to drugs.''
   No one knows it better than Vega, who said, ``I think (the judge)
gave me the best Christmas gift yet, to redeem my life back over.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881224-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0405EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Quake Bjt   12-24 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crews End Search For Survivors, Focus On Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for survivors of the
Armenian earthquake is over, and crews will now focus solely on
clearing away tons of concrete and debris so rebuilding can begin, a
government official said.
   No one has been found alive in the mountains of bricks,
splintered wood and steel since Thursday, when workers pulled a
woman from what used to be a building in Leninakan. She later died.
   ``We did everything to sift the ruins to save the lives of
whomever might be under them. At this time, we know that no one can
be alive,'' Vardkes Artsruny, a deputy prime minister of Armenia,
said in an interview Friday.
   ``The gigantic problem now is the cleanup,'' he said, speaking in
makeshift offices previously used as a children's center.
   Lights in the two-story relief headquarters sputtered as he spoke
because of the varying levels of power provided by portable
generators. During a blackout Friday, he met with agricultural
officials by candlelight.
   Fields around Leninakan, whose shoddy buildings collapsed when
the earth shook Dec. 7, are filled with debris. Twisted wire and
remains of stairs protrude from piles of formless rubble trucked
from the Armenian republic's second-largest city.
   Rescuers said a 16-year-old boy was found alive Monday, 12 days
after the quake, in the remains of a nine-story building. A bed
apparently shielded him from tons of concrete raining down.
   One of the boy's arms was broken. He asked rescuers to bandage
his eyes so he wouldn't be blinded when exposed to light after so
many days.
   Leninakan, on a mountain plateau near the Turkish border, had a
population of 280,000 before the quake. About 18,000 people were
found in the ruins, 8,000 of whom survived.
   Survivors taking part in the rescue, aided by 20,000 workers from
elsewhere in the Soviet Union and 15,000 soldiers, live in heated
tents sent from the Russian republic and in yurts, shepherds' tents
sent by Kazakhs and Mongols.
   Workers have nearly completed disinfecting and burying about
80,000 carcasses of cattle, sheep and pigs killed in villages, the
official news agency Tass reported.
   In a dispatch today, Tass estimated agricultural damage to
Armenia at about $3.2 billion. Of 342 populated areas in the quake
zone, 58 were destroyed, Tass said.
   Government officials have said Leninakan, Spitak and the dozens
of other cities and towns of northwestern Armenia destroyed by the
quake will be rebuilt in two years, but Artsruny said it may take
longer.
   ``It's not important that we reconstruct Leninakan in two years
and three months,'' he said. ``It's the fact that we're doing it.''
   Izvestia, the government newspaper, said Friday authorities had
not decided whether to rebuild Leninakan and Spitak on the same
sites or move them to nearby spots less susceptible to earthquakes.
   The quake has brought world figures to Armenia as well as
rescuers.
   President-elect George Bush's son and grandson are scheduled to
visit Armenia on Christmas Day to help distribute American aid. Jeb
Bush, 35, a Miami real estate developer, and his 12-year-old son,
George, will spend about six hours in Yerevan, according to Bush's
office in Washington.
   Most Armenians are devout Christians, but like other members of
Eastern churches, will celebrate Christmas on Jan. 6.
   U.S. aid has come in many forms. American volunteers are putting
up 100 plastic shelters at Spitak, and Tass said American
seismologists were establishing 25 earthquake monitoring stations in
the area of the quake's epicenter.
   In Washington, the American Red Cross said it would shift its
effort from immediate to long-term assistance, including buiding a
hospital. President Richard F. Schubert said the Red Cross has
received $3.5 million in cash contributions and pledges.
</TEXT>
