<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Crash-Biologist     12-24 0306</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Biologist,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renowned Biologist Among Flight 103 Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A renowned molecular biologist from Indiana
was among the passengers aboard Pan Am Flight 103 when it exploded
and crashed near Lockerbie, Scotland, killing everyone aboard.
   Irving S. Sigal, 35, was returning to his home in Pennington
Borough, N.J., when the plane crashed Wednesday, family members in
Indianapolis said. He had delivered a lecture before the Royal
Biochemical Society of London.
   Sigal was the senior director of molecular biology at the Merck
Sharp & Dohme Laboratories of Westpoint, Pa. Friends said his
principal area of concentration was in AIDS research.
   He had also made great strides in cancer research, having seen
both his parents die of cancer when he was young. His father, Dr.
Max V. Sigal, was a senior scientist at pharmaceutical giant Eli
Lilly and Co.
   Alvine Levine, a professor at Indiana University School of
Medicine, described Sigal as among the most brilliant people he had
ever known.
   ``After spending 35 years to prepare himself, he was just
arriving to where he could make a contribution to humanity, and now
he has been removed,'' said Levine. ``It is a loss in a dimension of
human values that is truly immeasurable.''
   Sigal attended North Central High School in Indianapolis and
graduated from Indiana University. He earned a Ph.D. in biochemistry
at Harvard University.
   After joining Merck in 1982, he established a program to study
the structure and function of proteins using techniques he had
helped develop. Family members said his work was leading to major
insights into the function of an oncogene protein, an enzyme that
plays a role in many human cancers.
   The dead also included several government officials, business
executives, 35 students taking part in a Syracuse University study
abroad program and others coming home for the holidays.
</TEXT>
