<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0645</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pacific Storm Pushes Rain, Snow into Oregon, Northern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The leading edge of a winter storm was spreading rain into
western Oregon and Northern California early today and was expected
to blow a white Christmas into several western states.
   Mild weather predominated east of the Rockies and rain covered a
wide part of the nation's midsection from southern Illinois to the
Gulf Coast.
   The Pacific Coast storm was expected to intensify today as it
moves inland, triggering storm warnings for snow and high winds in
several states.
   In Oregon and California, a winter storm warning was in effect
for the Cascade, Siskiyou, Shasta and Sierra Nevada mountains, and
for southwest and eastern sections of Oregon. Heavy snow was falling
in the mountains of Oregon early today.
   The coastal mountains of California could get 2 to 4 inches of
rain, with 1 to 2 feet of snow likely at elevations above 7,000 feet
and gusts of up to 50 mph forecast.
   A winter storm warning also was in effect for southern and
central Idaho, with winds up to 30 mph expected. A winter storm
warning also was in effect for the western mountains of Nevada.
   A low pressure system threatened Wisconsin with some heavy snow,
with up to 6 inches expected in the southern part of the state.
   Rain and fog covered much of the central and eastern states.
   A line of showers and thunderstorms extended from southern
Illinois to northern Louisiana. Thunderstorms in Arkansas produced
pea-size hail at Swifton and marble-size hail at Patterson late
Friday.
   Showers also doused extreme southern Florida early today and the
Carolina coast, and fog was widespread from the central Gulf Coast
to New England.
   Today's forecast called for rain and thunderstorms from the
eastern Great Lakes to western New England, the Middle Atlantic
states, the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the central Gulf Coast.
Rain also was likely along the northern and central Pacific Coast,
the central California valleys and Southern California.
   Snow was predicted in the Cascades of Washington and Oregon, the
Sierra Nevada in California, and in much of Nevada, Utah, Idaho and
eastern portions of Washington and Oregon. Snow also was forecast
for the upper Great Lakes and the lower Missouri Valley.
   Highs in the 30s or 40s were forecast for much of the nation.
Highs were expected to be in the 20s from the northern Plateau
through the central Rockies, the middle Missouri Valley into
northwest Wisconsin and western upper Michigan; between 10 and 20
degrees in the northern Plains and northern Minnesota; the 50s and
60s from the central and southern California coast through much of
Texas, the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys to the Middle Atlantic
coast; and in the 70s over southern Texas, along the Gulf Coast and
across Florida and southeast Georgia.
   At 2 a.m. EST, temperatures ranged from 3 degrees below zero at
Glasgow, Mont., to 73 degrees at Homestead and West Palm Beach, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 58 fog; Boston 34 fog; Buffalo 38 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 58 fog; Cincinnati 42 showery; Cleveland 34 fair;
Detroit 35 fair; Miami 72 partly cloudy; New York 38 fog;
Philadelphia 38 fog; Pittsburgh 36 cloudy; Portland, Maine 26 fog;
Washington 35 fog.
   _Central: Bismarck fair; Chicago 39 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth 51
fair; Denver 27 fair; Des Moines 33 rain; Indianapolis 40 cloudy;
Kansas City 41 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul 23 cloudy; Nashville 62
rain; New Orleans 69 fog; St. Louis 44 rain.
   _West: Albuquerque 25 partly cloudy; Anchorage fog; Las Vegas 36
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 51 cloudy; Phoenix 45 fair; Salt Lake
City 23 cloudy; San Diego 50 fair; San Francisco 45 rain; Seattle 38
rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 partly cloudy; Toronto 34 fair.
</TEXT>
