<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EcologistSlain     12-24 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecologist Slain,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amazon Ecologist Slain In Jungle Two Weeks After Threatened</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An internationally acclaimed
ecologist who led a fight to save Brazil's tropical forests was
ambushed and killed in a remote jungle village, police said.
   The victim, 44-year-old Francisco Mendes, said two weeks ago that
his life had been threatened.
   Mendes was shot Thursday night when he stepped outside his home
in Xapuri, a western village near the Bolivian border, said Federal
Police Chief Mauro Sposito.
   Mendes was playing dominos with friends and two police bodyguards
assigned to care for him when he went to take a shower in an outdoor
stall, Sposito said in a telephone interview from Rio Branco, 2,650
miles northwest of Rio de Janeiro.
   Moments later, Mendes was shot once in the upper chest with a
rifle at point-blank range, the chief said. The killers fled before
the bodyguards could leave the house, he said.
   The shooting occurred a half-block from the local police precinct.
   Police made no arrests and said there were no definite suspects.
   ``There was no way to stop them (the killers),'' Nilson Alves, a
Xapuri police officer, told The Associated Press by telephone. ``It
was starting to get dark, we only had one search lamp, and the
jungle is pretty thick in these parts.''
   Mendes was known worldwide for leading a campaign against Amazon
rain forest destruction. He was a representative for the World Bank
in Washington and other international lending institutions in
Britain and West Germany and tried to stop loans to Brazil for
development of the region.
   Mendes said he received repeated death threats for organizing
demonstrations against deforestation of the Amazon rain forest by
cattle ranchers and was under local police protection.
   In June 1987, he was honored by the United Nations for leading
members of a local union in a fight to preserve the Amazon jungle.
   The Rubber Tappers Union often staged peaceful ``empate,'' or
stalemate demonstrations, by standing in front of bulldozers with
family members and friends in areas where acres of forestland were
being cleared for grazing.
   Two union members were fatally shot in October.
   On Dec. 9, Mendes told a news conference in Rio de Janeiro he had
received death threats from Darly and Alvarnho Alves, brothers and
ranch owners who had past conflicts with the Rubber Tappers Union.
   The debate over how to develop the Amazon jungle, a vast expanse
of rain forest about two-fifths the size of the continental United
States, has led to frequent violence.
   Land disputes involving squatters, environmentalists and
landowners have caused about 250 deaths a year since 1985.
   Mendes, who is survived by a wife and two children, is to buried
today in Xapuri.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
