<DOCNO> AP881224-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0545EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MotherMurder     12-24 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mother Murder,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Throws Out Jury's Murder Verdict Against `Baby Blues' Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A murder conviction returned against a
mother who admitted killing her ailing son by running him over with
a car was rejected by a judge who said the woman was driven insane
by post-childbirth depression.
   Superior Court Judge Robert R. Fitzgerald, in announcing his
ruling, said he believed Sheryl Massip, 24, was made insane by what
some health experts call postpartum depression or ``baby blues.''
   ``I know people will say I've overstepped my bounds,'' Fitzgerald
told a stunned Orange County courtroom as he announced the decision
Friday. ``But the more I thought about it, the more I realized I
didn't have a choice but to find her insane. ... She was bonkers.''
   Prosecutors said they will review whether an appeal can be filed
on grounds that Fitzgerald's ruling went beyond his authority.
   ``We believe, on a cursory review of material, that he exceeded
his authority,'' Deputy District Attorney Tom Borris said. ``We
believe the best that he could have done is order a new trial.''
   Borris also said Fitzgerald didn't first inform attorneys about
his decision, as judges often do when they are about to issue a
reversal.
   The judge said afterward that he had not decided what the ruling
would be until the moment he delivered it.
   Ms. Massip, 24, had been convicted of second-degree murder.
Fitzgerald reduced the charge to voluntary manslaughter, but then
ruled that she was not guilty by reason of insanity, essentially
negating the voluntary manslaughter conviction.
   She still faces a maximum sentence of 11 years confinement in a
mental hospital. Her jury conviction called for 15 years to life in
prison.
   The judge ordered Ms. Massip to surrender Feb. 3 for at least 90
days of psychiatric observation. He then will decide if she needs
further treatment.
   Ms. Massip's family burst into cheers after the decision, which
came during a hearing originally scheduled for her sentencing on the
murder conviction.
   ``I couldn't have asked God for a better Christmas present,''
said Ms. Massip, who read a Bible before the decision. ``I got the
gift of life.''
   Her former husband, Alfredo Massip, whom she testified refused to
help care for the child, fled the court in tears and refused to talk
to reporters. He divorced Ms. Massip shortly after her arrest.
   During her trial, Ms. Massip admitted killing her 6-week old son,
Michael. But she testified that the child cried 15 to 18 hours a
day, adding that she heard voices telling her to put the infant out
of his misery.
   Experts summoned to testify by her lawyer said she had a severe
case of postpartum depression, brought on by hormonal imbalance
sometimes associated with childbirth.
   The rare disorder is believed to spur severe anxiety, delusions
and even violence in approximately three of every 1,000 new mothers.
   On April 29, 1987, Ms. Massip's 23rd birthday, she tried to toss
the child in front of a car near her Fullerton home, but the driver
swerved and missed him.
   She then beat the infant on the head and finally placed him
face-up under the tire of her Volvo station wagon and ran him over.
   After the killing, she first told investigators the child had
been stolen by a red-haired mystery woman with a gun.
   But the child's body was found in a trash can.
   ``The pain hasn't gone away. I have to live with the death of my
son, the loss of my son, for the rest of my life,'' Ms. Massip said
after the ruling. ``I pray that this doesn't happen to anyone else.''
   The judge's decision came after an impassioned plea from defense
attorney Milton Grimes.
   ``There's nothing in human experience that can justify what
Sheryl Massip did ... other than the fact that she was crazy at the
time,'' Grimes argued.
</TEXT>
