<1ST_LINE>u i PM-VacationingInvestigator     12-24 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vacationing Investigator,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transport Minister Vacationing During Crash Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British transportation minister Paul
Channon is vacationing in the Caribbean, drawing angry cries from
home because his department is in charge of investigating the Pan Am
jet crash in Scotland.
   ``It is unbelievable,'' said John Prescott of Britain's
opposition Labor Party on Friday, after Channon left for Barbados.
Channon and his wife, Ingrid, made no comment after landing later
Friday in Bridgetown.
   Channon was seen checking in with Mustique Airways and was
believed to be flying to Mustique, a tiny island about 40 miles away
that is a popular and exclusive getaway spot.
   ``It is quite intolerable and totally insensitive for the
transport secretary to leave for his holidays so soon after
Britain's worst aviation disaster, when bodies are still being
retrieved and a major security review is under way,'' said Prescott,
his party's transport spokesman.
   Investigators are still searching for dozens of bodies and for
clues to what caused Pan Am Flight 103 to break apart in the air
Wednesday night. The Boeing 747 plummeted into the Scottish village
of Lockerbie, killing all 258 people on board and leaving 20 people
on the ground missing and feared dead.
   The British Embassy in Barbados said it had no information on
Channon's visit because he was not on official business.
   In London, the Trade Ministry said Channon would be kept informed
on the investigation and planned to return soon after Christmas but
would fly home earlier if necessary.
   Prescott said Margaret Thatcher, the Conservative prime minister,
should ``call him back immediately'' and declared: ``Such lack of
judgment should justify his removal.''
   Geoffrey Dickens, a Conservative member of Parliament, said Labor
was ``trying to make capital out of other people's misery and
death.''
</TEXT>
