<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PlayClosing     12-24 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Play Closing,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Play Closing after Co-Producer Recently Disclosed To Be In Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Broadway comedy ``Checkmates'' is to close
Jan. 1, less than three weeks after it was revealed that a
co-producer is serving a 28-years-to-life prison term in
California's San Quentin for attempted murder.
   The United States Attorney's office in Los Angeles has also
indicted the co-producer, Michael Harris, on drug conspiracy charges.
   The play, a comedy about two married couples in an apartment
building, opened Aug. 4 and will have had 177 regular performances
and 17 previews when it closes. It stars Ruby Dee, Paul Winfield,
Denzel Washington and Marsha Jackson.
   A production spokesman, Adrian Bryan-Brown, said poor box-office
receipts led the show's two remaining producers to decide to close
it. The decision was also based on Washington's intention to leave
the show to do a movie, and his stand-by's television project, the
spokesman said.
   Harris, 26, who with a partner put up half of the $770,000 it
cost to take the show to Broadway, received producer's billing on
posters for the comedy until it was revealed earlier this month that
he had been convicted of killing a man he accused of stealing from a
drug operation.
   The play was originally produced in Los Angeles by Harris and
Hayward Collins. When it opened in New York, its producers also
included James M. Nederlander, James L. Nederlander and Philip Rose.
The Nederlanders withdrew in September after disappointing reviews
and ticket sales.
</TEXT>
