<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO-Shiites     12-24 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO-Shiites,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO, Shiite Militia Make New Peace Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Mieh Mieh is correct</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and
the Shiite Moslem Amal militia have reached a new peace pact to end
their bloody 3-year conflict, Beirut newspapers reported today.
   The papers published the 11-point pact, which is the sixth since
1985 when Amal moved against Palestinian refugee camps to prevent
PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat from rebuilding a power base in Lebanon.
   The five earlier accords fell apart, and there is widespread
doubt the latest accord will hold.
   More than 3,000 people have been killed and 10,000 wounded in the
Amal-PLO conflict.
   Amal has an estimated 10,000 armed militiamen. The PLO has 4,500
guerrillas based in the Sidon region, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   Syria, which supports Amal, last month withdrew 66 truce
observers from the highlands east of Sidon. That raised fears of
major clashes, but so far only localized skirmishes have occurred.
   The new pact provides for a disengagement of forces and the
removal of frontline barricades to enforce a cease-fire between Amal
and the PLO around Sidon, provincial capital of south Lebanon.
   The conflict has centered on the city and its environs since
Arafat's fighters were driven out of their strongholds in Beirut's
refugee camps by rival Syrian-backed Palestinian factions in July,
something Amal had failed to do.
   Amal and the PLO pledged in the accord to resolve friction by
peaceful means and reopen all roads in the region for unrestricted
movement.
   The accord stipulated that Amal should lift its 3-year siege of
the Rashadiyeh refugee camp in the southern port of Tyre. About
18,000 Palestinians live there.
   It also provided for repairing the devastation in Sidon's Ein
el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh camps and repatriating thousands of
displaced Palestinians and Shiites in the region.
   The leftist Sunni Moslem Nasserite militia, which has stayed
neutral in the Amal-PLO conflict, will oversee the new cease-fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
