<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HelicopterSuit     12-24 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Suit,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daughter of Reporter Killed in Helicopter Crash Gets $325,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The daughter of a radio traffic reporter who was
killed in a helicopter crash while on the air will receive $325,000
in a settlement rather than face the agony of a trial, her lawyer
says.
   Naomi Knickerbocker, 19, is the only child of reporter Jane
Dornacker, 39, who was killed in 1986.
   Miss Knickerbocker's attorney, James Molesky of Oakland, Calif.,
said a court fight might have gained his client more money, but said
she wanted to dispose of the matter because, she said, her mother's
``tragic death has been most difficult and painful'' for her.
   The settlement was approved Dec. 14 by Manhattan Surrogate Court
Judge Marie M. Lambert. It was disclosed on Friday.
   Ms. Dornacker, who came to New York from San Francisco, was
broadcasting a traffic report for WNBC radio when the helicopter in
which she was riding crashed into the Hudson River.
   As the chopper plunged toward a pier, listeners heard Ms.
Dornacker scream at the pilot, ``Hit the water! Hit the water!''
   Ms. Dornacker's body was pulled from the submerged helicopter
about 10 minutes later.
   Spectrum Helicopters of Ridgefield Park, N.J., owners and
operators of the crashed aircraft, will pay $250,000 of the
settlement. The remaining $75,000 will be paid by Enstrom Helicopter
Corp. of Menominee, Mich., manufacturers of the chopper, and the
Formsprag Industrial Power Transmission division of Dana Corp.,
makers of the helicopter's failed transmission.
</TEXT>
