<1ST_LINE>u i PM-China-TrainWreck     12-24 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Train Wreck,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Crashes Into Bus, At Least 45 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger train bound for Beijing crashed into a
bus packed with peasants, killing at least 45 people and injuring
67, national television reported today.
   The accident, in northeastern China's Liaoning province, occurred
Friday at about 8 p.m., the news program said.
   The report said 84 peasants were heading home to Inner Mongolia
when the bus they were riding in crossed the railroad tracks in
Liaoning.
   The Dandong-to-Beijing train crashed into the bus, crushing the
vehicle, the report said. The locomotive also left the track and
overturned.
   The TV showed a row of bodies and said many of the injured were
in critical condition. It said police were investigating the cause
of the accident. The report did not specify whether all the dead
were from the bus.
   The report also showed the bus, which was mangled almost beyond
recognition.
   Train service was restored to the line this morning, the report
said.
   So far this year, there have been four other major train wrecks,
including a derailment in Yunnan province in January that left 88
dead.
</TEXT>
