<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PLO     12-24 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat, PLO Leaders Meet For Crucial Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yasser Arafat and the PLO's executive
committee gathered today for a meeting to discuss forming a
provisional government for the newly declared independent
Palestinian state.
   The closed-door meeting was scheduled amid growing opposition by
radical Palestinian factions and some figures within the Palestine
Liberation Organization to Arafat's recent peace initiative.
   The PLO chairman has explicitly recognized Israel and renounced
terrorism.
   PLO officials said Arafat met with senior aides in the Iraqi
capital before the meeting.
   Sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the 15-member
committee will discuss last week's talks between the PLO and the
United States, efforts to convene an international Middle East peace
conference, and the formation of the provisional Palestinian
government.
   The PLO chief in Baghdad, Azzam al-Ahmad, told The Associated
Press on Friday that the executive committee will also review the
year-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied territories
and ``ways of escalating resistance to the occupation forces.''
   The sources said the provisional government might not be named
during the meeting of the executive committee because ``further
consultations may be needed.''
   The Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliament-in-exile,
declared the Palestinian state at a meeting last month.
   Scores of countries have recognized the still-symbolic
Palestinian state. PLO officials said that while Arafat is in
Baghdad, he will lay the cornerstone of a Palestinian embassy
building in the Iraqi capital.
   Arafat arrived in Baghdad late Friday after flying from Rome,
where he met with Pope John Paul II and with Italian Prime Minister
Ciriaco De Mita and Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti.
   Those attending the Baghdad meeting included Mustafa el-Zibri,
deputy leader of the Marxist Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, who has bitterly condemned Arafat's moves.
   El-Zibri is the front's sole representative on the executive
committee, which includes three members of Arafat's mainstream Fatah
faction, the biggest of the several guerrilla groups in the PLO.
   Those groups are also represented on the committee, which
includes various other non-guerrilla Palestinian organizations and
independents.
   The front's leader, George Habash, reluctantly endorsed Arafat's
moves at the Palestine National Council meeting to preserve unity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
