<DOCNO> AP881224-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0813EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-TaxBattle 1stLd-Writethru   12-24 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Tax Battle, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0491,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Tax Reform Package</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS graf 8 beginning: After the ... to show Takeshita
took over acting finance portfolio. Picks up graf 9 beginning:
`Tatsuo Murayama ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's bid to reform the
tax system today cleared its last hurdle when the upper house of
parliament passed the measures after 24 hours of delaying tactics by
opposition parties.
   The new laws give Japan a 3 percent sales tax and reduce its
heavy reliance on direct taxes by cutting corporate and upper-level
income taxes. The legislation is to take effect April 1.
   Opposition parties introduced censure motions against Takeshita
and four other government officials Friday afternoon and then
shuffled to the podium at a snail's pace to delay voting.
   The tactics carried parliament through its first overnight
session in 13 years. Opposition parties have blocked previous
attempts by other premiers to overhaul the tax system, which was
drafted by U.S. occupation authorities in the lean years after
Japan's defeat in World War II.
   Voting on the tax bills took place more than 24 hours after the
censure motions were introduced. Legislators from the Japan
Socialist and Japan Communist parties left the chamber in a show of
protest, and the bills were quickly approved by the majority Liberal
Democrats.
   Since the Takeshita administration formally submitted the tax
reform package to Parliament in July, opposition legislators led by
the Japan Socialist Party and Japan Communist Party have boycotted
sessions, demanding the government first fully investigate a
high-level stock-trading scandal.
   The scandal, involving Takeshita and other top officials who
profited from questionable sales of unlisted stocks bought at
bargain prices, has led to the resignations of politicians, business
leaders and media executives, including Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa, who stepped down on Dec. 9.
   Takeshita took over the finance portfolio then.
   Tatsuo Murayama was one of the chief architects of the tax reform
package.
   A former Finance Ministry bureaucrat, he is a considered a tax
specialist and played a leading role in the Liberal Democratic
Party's tax review committee, which he has chaired since 1985.
   The Communist Party and local business groups on Friday protested
the sales tax at a rally in Takeshita's hometown.
   About 100 people shouting ``Destroy the tax bill'' and calling
for the resignation of the Cabinet marched near the Takeshita
family's sake brewery in Kakeai-cho in western Shimane prefecture,
organizer Jiro Wada said.
   A study by the Shimouma Consumers' Cooperative Association, a
Tokyo consumers' group, says that under the new tax plan, a typical
four-member household with an annual income of $53,225 will pay
$1,305 less in income and residents' taxes, but the new sales tax
will cost it an additional $500.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
