<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Christmas 1stLd-Writethru a0462 12-24 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Christmas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Streets Empty In The Biblical City Of Bethlehem</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with annual procession, details. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HAITHAM HAMAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHLEHEM, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The streets of Bethlehem
were nearly deserted today as hundreds of Israeli soldiers set up
checkpoints to prevent Christmas violence.
   As Christmas eve began in the biblical town, the bishop of
Jerusalem entered the Church of the Nativity, which marks the site
where the Bible says Jesus was born, amid the smoke of incense and a
crowd of Israeli security men.
   The bishop, Michel Sabbah, was greeted in rain-drenched Manger
Square by the Israeli military governor of Bethlehem, Lt. Col.
Shaltiel Lavy, and the city's Palestinian mayor, Elias Freij.
   Christian pilgrims seemed to be outnumbered by hundreds of
Israeli police and troops and dozens of journalists as Sabbah was
greeted under a tradition that goes back to when the region was
governed by British and Turkish rulers.
   Sabbah, the Roman Catholic patriarch, was led into the church in
a procession headed by the traditional Moslem guides in red fezzes
banging large canes on the ancient stones outside the church.
   Holy water was sprinkeld at the door of the church as Sabbah
entered, surrounded by other church officials and altar boys.
   Israeli police formed a path holding hands to keep back
journalists and others trying to get a glimpse of Sabbah in his red
robe.
   Freij said that despite the sparse number of tourists during the
day he expected that St. Catherine's Church, next to the Church of
the Nativity and where midnight Mass will be said, would be full of
pilgrims by evening.
   Asked about his message to the world on Christmas eve, Freij said:
   ``We say to God on the highest, peace on earth. My message is
that we want peace with our Israeli neighbors so both Arabs and Jews
can live in peace and security as good friends, as free people, as
equal people.''
   Only one coffee stand was open in Manger Square. The other
restaurants and tourist shops closed because of a strike declared by
the PLO-backed leaders of the year-old uprising against Israel's
occupation.
   Security was tight around Manger Square. Anyone wanting to enter
had to pass through metal detectors and be searched by Israeli
security men.
   The Rev. Stephen Doyle, a Franciscan priest from a nearby
ecumenical research center, said he thought the security might
discourage Palestinian Christians from attending midnight Mass. Many
Arab Christians have said they will not attend Mass because of the
strike.
   Leaders of the Palestinian uprising have asked Christian Arabs to
boycott Mass to show their solidarity with the more than 330 people
who have been killed during the rebellion. Fourteen Israelis also
have been slain.
   ``We will punish everybody who leaves his house,'' said a slogan
painted in red on one town wall. ``Let's make this day a mourning
day for our martyrs'' said another, which was signed by the pro-PLO
underground leadership.
   Freij and other city officials decided to cancel a traditional
parade by Boy Scouts during the evening ceremonies in sympathy with
the uprising.
   ``This is Christmas, but there will be no celebration or
decorations and the Christmas trees will not be put up,'' Freij said
on Israel radio.
   ``The whole mood of the West Bank is one of anger, sorrow,
frustration and anxiety,'' he said.
   Doyle was asked if he thought the cancellation of festivities was
a good idea on Christmas eve.
   ``I think they are right on target,'' said the Philadelphia-born
priest. ``There is a memory to celebrate, but the present reality is
very depressing.''
   Jean Holladay, a visitor from Wheelock, Vt., said she thought the
heavy media and security presence interfered with the holiday spirit.
   ``I think the situation here has a numbing effect on Christmas,''
she said. ``All I see now are TV people and soldiers.''
   In Nablus, 25 miles north of Bethlehem, a 21-year-old Arab man
who was shot in the head by soldiers during a demonstration last
week died of his wounds.
   A 55-year-old man from the nearby village of Ijah was shot in the
left leg during a demonstration today.
   In the Gaza Strip, stores were shut and the army closed three
schools after students set up rock barricades in the street and
pelted soldiers with stones.
   A 15-year-old boy from Gaza's Jebaliya refugee camp was shot in
the right leg after a clash with troops. He was taken to Ahli Arab
hospital and discharged after the bullet was removed.
</TEXT>
