<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 0930EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-CivilServants     12-24 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Civil Servants,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Employees Chosen After China's First Large-Scale Civil
Service Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The southern province of Guangdong has held
communist China's first civil service examination, and 11,000 of the
120,000 applicants were selected for government employment, a report
said today.
   The examination in September was reminiscent of the system used
in imperial China, where civil servants also were selected through
tests.
   In present-day China, however, the functions of Communist Party
and government officials often overlap, and political connections
frequently play a role in obtaining jobs and promotions.
   Last year, Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang proposed a civil
service system, suggesting government employees not engaged in
political work should obtain jobs on the basis of an examination,
and wages and promotions should depend on merit.
   ``The idea of giving priority to seniority and other worn-out
concepts that stifle people's initiative and creativity should be
eradicated,'' he said.
   The Guangdong examination was ``a prelude to the civil service
system,'' said the independent Ming Pao newspaper, quoting the
pro-government China News Service.
   The examination was adminstered to 120,000 people in an ``open,
fair and competitive'' manner, the report said.
   About 11,000 applicants passed the examination, including
workers, high school and university graduates, and 3,000 people from
rural areas, the report said. It did not give a breakdown of
participants by age or sex.
   The new employees will work in provincial departments, including
security, courts, finance and revenue, the report said.
</TEXT>
