<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Colombia-Escape     12-24 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Colombia-Escape,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Helicopter Attacks Colombian Prison, Frees Five</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armed men landed a helicopter in the
central yard of a Colombian prison, fired at guards and flew away
with at least five inmates connected to cocaine gangs, police said
today.
   Leonel Cruz Chaparro, warden at the Bellavista prison, said the
raid occurred Friday as about 600 inmates and their families were
celebrating Christmas in the prison yard.
   The pilot, identified as Nestor Morales, was injured and arrested
minutes later as he landed alone at the Olaya Herrera airport in
this city 170 miles northwest of Bogota.
   Police launched a manhunt for the fugitives, who were apparently
dropped off somewhere between the prison and the airport, officials
said.
   Nobody was injured on the ground, Cruz Chaparro said.
   Police said the helicopter, stolen from the private company
Helicol, landed at the yard, picked up at least five inmates and
flew away.
   The fugitives included two members of the Los Nachos gang, a
Colombian group that has been linked to killings ordered by the
Medellin cartel, which is believed responsible for most of the
cocaine smuggled into the United States.
   Commandos twice have tried to raid the Bellavista prison this
year in attempts to free prisoners. Prison guards thwarted both
attacks.
