<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Prison Riot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0469,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prison Riot Over Christmas Pardon Denial Kills 22</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with 22 dead, other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TEPIC, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An uprising by inmates who were denied
Christmas pardons was crushed by police, but 22 people, including
the prison warden, died in gunfights between authorities and
prisoners, officials said today.
   The incident began Thursday at the Venustiano Carranza
penitentiary in Nayarit state, when about six inmates took 12 to 14
prison employees hostage. It ended about 11 p.m. Friday when two
commando teams stormed the prison.
   ``The total counted this morning is 22 dead and five or maybe six
people seriously injured. Four, including the penitentiary director,
were killed before special forces stormed the place. Eighteen were
killed when the commandos stormed the place,'' a police officer who
demanded anonymity.
   He didn't break the death toll down into prisoners and employees.
   Another officer, Sergio Anzaldo, said: ``There was a fierce
gunfight lasting about 15 minutes before the special forces could
quell the mutiny.''
   Anzaldo, who was the duty officer when the commandos attacked,
said everything was quiet in the penitentiary today. ``The guard has
been doubled and reinforced with special elements,'' he said in a
telephone interview.
   The chain of events in Tepic, 500 miles northwest of Mexico City,
began when about six inmates who had sought appointments with the
warden arrived at his prison office Thursday, said Francisco Flores,
a state government spokesman. At the same time, two well-dressed
visitors posing as lawyers approached the building, according to the
spokesman.
   The men posing as attorneys entered the prison without being
searched, then took out guns, Flores said. It was not immediately
clear who started the shooting, which Flores said ended in three
deaths.
   The dead included warden Samuel Alvarado, 31, who bled to death
from a leg wound, a security guard, and an inmate _ the brother of
the apparent leader of the assault _ officials said.
   The prisoners, angry that they were denied Christmas pardons for
good behavior, seized hostages, and Flores said about 200 soldiers,
police and guards surrounded the penitentiary.
   As dusk fell Friday, Mexico City's Zorro and Escorpion commando
teams sprayed tear gas and rushed the prison, causing what Flores
called a ``very violent confrontation.'' The ensuing violence more
people dead, including the head of the Zorro commando team, he said.
   Three hours later, the commandos staged a second raid, which
killed more people and ended up freeing the hostages, he said.
   On Friday the prisoners demanded an armored car and high-powered
firearms with the apparent intention of leaving the place, then
canceled the demand.
   Except for the few inmates holding hostages in the administrative
offices, the rest of the prison's 1,200 inmates remained under
control, Flores said. He said the mutinous prisoners included people
serving time on drug charges.
   Flores said the state attorney general, Rodolfo Leon, tried to
talk the mutineers _ who had guns, knives and clubs _ out of further
violence. He said the inmates appeared to be uncertain of what they
wanted to do.
</TEXT>
