<DOCNO> AP881224-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1026EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ryzhkov Bjt   12-24 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ryzhkov, Bjt,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Where's Gorbachev? Kremlin's No. 2 Man Thrust Into Limelight</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov, considered a stodgy
technocrat, has suddenly been thrust into the public eye during the
disaster caused by the Armenian earthquake.
   The Soviet Union's dynamic leader, President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, has retreated into an unusual silence and been absent
from public view after making a brief trip to Armenia.
   Ryzhkov went to Armenia the morning after the Dec. 7 earthquake.
Until he returned to Moscow last week, Ryzhkov received heavy
coverage in the state-run media doing the things Soviets have come
to expect from the more voluble Gorbachev.
   Ryzhkov directed the machinery of government in full view of TV
cameras, hugged homeless Armenians and met crowds on street corners.
   Gorbachev, by contrast, rushed home from New York, spent a stormy
weekend in Armenia and has not been seen in public since Dec. 11.
   There were no indications that Ryzhkov's prominence and
Gorbachev's absence signaled any realignment in the Kremlin or that
Gorbachev was ill. But it was suddenly Ryzhkov who represented the
Kremlin throughout the burst of publicity given by the Soviet media
to the earthquake.
   The careers of Gorbachev and Ryzhkov have been linked. Ryzhkov
was appointed to the Communist Party Politburo in April 1985, a
month after Gorbachev took power. He was assigned to head the Soviet
government in September 1985, and is considered an important player
in Gorbachev's economic reform plans.
   But the earthquake _ and Gorbachev's absence _ gave the
59-year-old Ryzhkov an opportunity to shed a colorless image and
gain daily television exposure.
   ``Thank you, thank you, thank you,'' Armenians called to Ryzhkov
in the earthquake-damaged city of Kirovakan. ``People are very
satisfied,'' said an elderly woman, pressing Ryzhkov's hands.
   Ryzhkov responded to people with smiles and promises of help.
   ``He's gotten a high profile, but whether it works to his
advantage, I don't know,'' said one diplomat who spoke on condition
of anonymity. That will depend on how Ryzhkov's work in Armenia is
perceived by other Kremlin leaders, he said.
   Ryzhkov acknowledged widespread reports of disorganization in the
relief efforts during a news conference in the Armenian capital
Yerevan on Dec. 12. But he said after a bad start the organization
had begun to improve.
   In the spirit of Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or greater
openness, Ryzhkov directly answered all the questions put to him by
foreign and Soviet reporters in Yerevan.
   He showed little emotion in his answers. But when reporters asked
him about ethnic troubles between Armenians and Azerbaijanis over
control of the Nagorno-Karabakh region, he began jabbing the air
with his hand and said, ``We don't understand these people. While
the whole country is helping them, they are raising these questions.
We think the Armenian people must reject them.''
   It was the same issue that caused Gorbachev to show his anger on
Soviet television. Asked about allegations by Armenian activists
that Soviet officials planned to move orphaned Armenians out of the
earthquake area and repopulate it with Russians, he responded,
``What kind of morals do those people have?''
   ``They don't need Karabakh. They are waging a battle for power,
and they must be stopped,'' Gorbachev said.
   Many Armenians are upset with Gorbachev for refusing to give in
to their demands to annex Nagorno-Karabakh from Azerbaijan.
   Gorbachev's absence from public view was ``normal for the week
after the quake, but this week it's a little more difficult to
explain,'' said the foreign diplomat.
   But Gorbachev has not missed any events that could be considered
important enough to demand his presence, and the Kremlin has
continued issuing documents over Gorbachev's name.
   The Tass news agency said Gorbachev sent a message of condolence
to President Reagan after the crash of a Pan Am jet in Scotland on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
