<DOCNO> AP881224-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1033EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GraffitiArrest     12-24 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Graffiti Arrest,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-Ager Seen Writing Graffiti Signature, Allowing for Double
Prosecution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A graffiti artist's distinctive signature became
his downfall when police matched the one he was writing on a
Manhattan building with one that appeared on nearly 80 subway cars,
authorities said.
   Transit police saw the teen-ager writing graffiti on the building
and were able to charge him with defacing the subway cars because
the graffiti signatures, or ``tags,'' matched, said Al O'Leary, a
Transit police spokesman.
   Todd S. James, 19, was charged with second-degree criminal
mischief, first-degree criminal tampering, both felonies, and a
misdemeanor, third-degree criminal trespass, O'Leary said Friday.
   If convicted, James faces four to seven years in prison on each
felony count.
   The officers saw James spraying the letters REAS on the building,
O'Leary said. Last weekend, 160 subway cars were spraypainted,
nearly half of them with the letters REAS.
   ``This can be in the future, if the prosecution is successful, a
very valuable tool in the war against vandalism,'' O'Leary said.
``It's the first time the district attorney's office was able to
prosecute without seeing him being in the act of graffiti-ing the
property.
   ``A tag to a graffiti vandal is like a signature,'' he said.
``The way you sign your paycheck is the way a graffiti vandal writes
his or her name on public property.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
