<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Tanker     12-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Tanker,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Loose Oil Storage Vessel Drifts 13 Miles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant oil storage vessel broke its
mooring and drifted for 13 miles on Saturday, forcing a shutdown of
more than 10 percent of Britain's North Sea oil production, coast
guard and oil company officials said.
   Two tugboats sent to the scene, about 200 miles east of the
Scottish port of Dundee, managed to attach lines to the tanker and
brought the vessel under control after five hours, said the Coast
Guard Rescue and Coordination Center in Aberdeen.
   The converted 200,000-ton tanker with 34 men on board was being
towed by the tugs, the Oil Chancellor and the Oil Challenger, the
coast guard said. Its destination was not immediately known.
   The vessel is a tanker modified to act as a fixed, engineless
floating storage tank. It has been permanently moored in Shell UK's
Fulmar oilfield, collecting oil from three fields and then loading
the crude on to smaller tankers.
   Shell UK said production from the three fields _ the Fulmar and
neighboring Auk and Clyde platforms _ had been shut down
automatically when the vessel broke free.
   The three fields have a combined daily production of 210,000
barrels of crude _ 10 to 12 percent of total output from the British
sector of the North Sea, said a Shell spokesman. He spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Shell said production from the three fields would remain shut
because they now had nowhere to send their oil. Crude oil from the
three platforms normally flows by pipeline along the seabed and
feeds into the vessel, known as a Floating Storage Unit.
   When the vessel broke free at about 5:30 a.m. in 15-foot seas and
60-knot winds, Shell said it dragged its mooring installation with
it.
   Shell said a ``sizable'' amount of oil had been spotted in the
area, but it was not known whether a serious leak had developed.
   When the system shut down automatically at the seabed, Shell said
there were 370 cubic yards of oil in the pipeline beyond the
shutdown point.
   Initially, there were fears the vessel would collide with other
installations in the North Sea. With the vessel under tow,
helicopters called out from Scotland and northern England to
evacuate the men if necessary were recalled.
</TEXT>
