<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ElizabethDoleProfile     12-24 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elizabeth Dole Profile,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elizabeth Dole: Southern Belle With Ivy League Credentials</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Hanford Dole, first and perhaps the
only woman named to the Bush cabinet, has the resume of a topnotch
Ivy League lawyer and the charm of a quintessential Southern belle.
   Her ability to disarm even the toughest critics has earned her
widespread popularity on Capital Hill, even among many Democrats.
And her reputation as an able government official appears to have
weathered harsh evaluations of her Reagan administration tenure as
transportation secretary.
   ``She is a woman of great ability with many friends in both
parties on Capitol Hill,'' said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
chairman of the Labor and Human Resources Committee that must
confirm her.
   Saturday she was named as labor secretary by President-elect
Bush. The choice left just one Cabinet spot open, that of energy
secretary.
   Relentlessly cheerful, Mrs. Dole is at age 52 half of what inside
Washington likes to call a ``power couple.'' Her husband is Senate
Republican Leader Robert Dole, who unsuccessfully sought his party's
presidential nomination. They have a Watergate apartment and a
miniature schnauzer named ``Leader.''
   Known as ``Liddy,'' a nickname she picked herself, Mrs. Dole was
born in Salisbury, N.C., the only daughter of John Van Hanford, a
small-town florist, and Mary Ella Hanford. Early on, she displayed a
promising combination of brains and beauty.
   Growing up, she had ballet classes, horseback riding lessons and
at 18, a debutante ball in Raleigh. At 20, she was student body
president of the Women's College at Duke University and also May
Queen. She graduated Phi Beta Kappa with a bachelor's degree in
history from Duke in 1958 and went on to receive a master's degree
in education and government from Harvard University in 1960.
   In 1962 she was named beauty queen at a Boston naval base,
although she later recalled: ``I was getting a little old for this
sort of thing.'' She graduated from Harvard Law School in 1965.
   Washington, her mother said, drew Mrs. Dole ``like a magnet.''
She immersed herself for 20 years in the process of climbing the
political ladder. In the process, she switched from Democrat to
Independent to Republican.
   She made her way through the old Department of Health, Education
and Welfare, the Federal Trade Commission and President Nixon's
Commission on Consumer Interests. In 1976 she took a leave of
absence from the FTC to campaign for her husband's vice presidential
bid and in 1979, she quit the FTC two years before her term expired
to help him run for president.
   Mrs. Dole is generally credited with softening her husband's
hatchet-man image, although she dismisses that, seeming to suggest
he was always really a softy: ``He's sort of the way I always knew
him.''
   With no prior background in the transportation field, Mrs. Dole
was named in 1983 as President Reagan's transportation secretary.
She pushed for mandatory seat belt laws, tighter screening
procedures in airports and more sophisticated anti-collision devices
for airliners.
   But she was criticized in Congress for spending more time on
press releases than real improvements. Critics contended she more
often than not unveiled new regulatory procedures after the
department had been pushed into it by Congress or the courts.
Critics also faulted her for approving a string of airline mergers
that concentrated much of the airline industry into a half-dozen
large carriers.
   In 1987, a trade journal called her DOT stewardship ``little more
than a planned media event.'' And The Washington Monthly headlined a
cover story: ``Charming Her Way to the White House; air travel
stinks, auto safety's a joke and Washington still loves Liddy Dole.''
   Mrs. Dole stepped down a year ago to help her husband's
presidential campaign, saying the move had nothing to do with the
criticism and declaring she was glad to join him on the campaign
trail after years of living ``like passing ships in the night.''
   Sen. Dole noted her new appointment with a combination of pride
and humor. ``It looks like TV dinners for me again, but I'll still
probably vote for her confirmation,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
