<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Stripper-Impersonation     12-24 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stripper-Impersonation,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Of Impersonating Officer Dropped Against Stripper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The women at the birthday party enjoyed
watching a male stripper shuck his fake sheriff's deputy outfit, but
police gave him a different reception on his way home.
   Charles Bateham, 27, was charged with impersonating a police
officer. The charges were later dropped, but Bateham suffered a
separated shoulder in a motorcycle accident prior to his arrest.
   The stripper started off his act Oct. 16 wearing a fake sheriff's
deputy uniform with ``Sarasota Sheriff's Office'' patches on the
arms, a mail-order ``County Mounty'' badge and a gun belt.
   After performing at the birthday party, Bateham said he put a
jacket over his uniform and was driving toward his girlfriend's
house when a police car started following him. He had an accident on
a dead end road.
   ``When (the officers) walked up to me, I told them I was a dancer
and it was a BB gun. One reached over and threw the gun on the
ground, and the rest is history.''
   When he arrived in court Thursday to stand trial, he learned the
misdemeanor charge was being dropped.
   Defense attorney Ty Trayner said a person cannot be convicted of
impersonating a police officer just because he is dressed for the
part. He has to try something official, like threaten to arrest
somebody.
   So Bateham is free to continue using the uniform with Male
Express.
   ``The deputy uniform is our most popular outfit,'' he said.
``I'll just take more precautions from now on. I won't wear the
shirt or gun belt when I'm traveling.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
