<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietChristmas     12-24 0584</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Christmas,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Russian `Grandfather Frost' For Hire At Christmas, New Year's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet holiday customs look a lot like American
ones, but in Moscow, the jolly man with the fluffy white beard and
red suit rides in a taxi and few of the presents he brings run on
batteries.
   Instead of standing in line at a shopping mall to sit on Santa's
lap, many Soviet children get house calls from Ded Moroz _
Grandfather Frost _ and Snegurochka, a beautiful snow maiden dressed
in white.
   Five-year-old Olga's eyes lit up as Ded Moroz and Snegurochka
walked into her family's apartment Saturday morning.
   The couple sang, danced and told riddles with the little girl.
Ded Moroz then opened his sack and pulled out a huge teddy bear,
which Olga's father had handed him secretly beforehand.
   ``It's so beautiful,'' said Olga, who was dressed in a
powder-blue princess costume and wore a shiny tiara and a big light
blue bow atop her head.
   Ded Moroz and Snegurochka wished the family happy New Year and
trudged through the mounds of snow back to their hired yellow taxi.
They had about 30 more stops before the day was through.
   ``I don't feel like it's New Year's unless I dress up like this
and visit little children,'' said Vladimir Krylov, 37, who has been
playing Ded Moroz for nine years.
   ``Our (Soviet) children believe so much that Ded Moroz and
Snegurochka are real,'' said Lyuda Golubgikova, 33, a six-year
veteran Snegurochka. ``I love to see their eyes shine when we walk
in.''
   After the Bolshevik revolution in 1917, the primary winter
holiday in the Soviet Union switched from Christmas, celebrated Jan.
7 in the Russian Orthodox faith, to New Year's.
   Olga's parents were among about 4,000 people who each paid a
Moscow business called Consumer Services about $9 to have the
holiday couple bring New Year's greetings to their children between
Dec. 24 and Jan. 5, said Tamara Korovina, who hired the cast of
characters.
   People signed up for Ded Moroz house calls at Detsky Mir, the
largest children's store in the Soviet Union, located in the center
of Moscow.
   Soviets flock to Detsky Mir from across the nation and buy about
500,000 toys per day during the holiday season, said Garnik
Oganesyan, director of commerce at the five-story store.
   Valentina Rubin, 31, went to Detsky Mir to pick up a toy for her
3-year-old son, but while shopping decided to order a visit from Ded
Moroz.
   ``Andrusha will be so surprised! He has only seen Ded Moroz on
greeting cards,'' she said.
   Mrs. Rubin said she had no trouble finding the toy submarine her
son had requested. All she had to do was fight the crowd at Detsky
Mir _ which makes Christmas Eve at a New York department store look
calm in comparison _ and wait in line for 30 minutes.
   Parents whose children asked for electronic or battery-operated
toys were likely to be disappointed. Detsky Mir only had a few such
toys, and as soon as they went on display they were snapped up,
admitted Oganesyan.
   ``My 11-year-old son wants an electronic game, but I don't think
I'll be able to find it,'' said a Detsky Mir employee, who asked
that her name not be used.
   She said Soviet children usually receive just one toy, ``because
for each gift a parent must run, run, run to find it and then wait,
wait, wait to buy it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
