<DOCNO> AP881224-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1220EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Crash-Profiles Bjt   12-24 0773</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Profiles, Bjt,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stories Behind The Names of Those Aboard Pan Am Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The world knows them as victims, but family members and friends
knew the 258 people who boarded Pan Am Flight 103 in London as sons
and daughters, husbands and wives, students, teachers, doctors and
businessmen. Here are brief sketches of the people they remember:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   At the Justice Department in Washington, flags were ordered flown
at half-staff in memory of Michael Bernstein, an attorney with the
agency's Office of Special Investigations. Bernstein, a 36-year-old
father of two, had been in Austria negotiating a treaty to allow
some former Nazis in the United States to be deported there.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jim Pitt, 24, of South Hadley, Mass., had been studying in
Germany and had planned to go on a different flight, but at the last
minute decided to fly with a friend to London, his family said. Pitt
called home and left a message that he would be on the Pan Am
flight, said his mother, Sallie Hughes Pitt. She said Pitt was a
champion fencer and a poet who wrote long letters home regularly.
``He would call me up and say, `How're you doing, Mom? I was
thinking about you today.' He did that just last week and said he
was looking forward to coming home,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Nineteen-year-old twins Jason and Eric Coker of Mendham Township,
N.J., were participants in a Syracuse University study aboard
program. Both played soccer and ran track.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The pilot, James MacQuarrie, 55, of Kensington, N.H., was
orphaned as a child. His widow asked that Americans observe a moment
of silence at 1 p.m. on Christmas to remember the victims.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Shannon Davis, 19, was a junior at Syracuse University majoring
in child and family studies and planned to open a day-care center.
Her older sister, Whitney Davis, said, ``Shannon was sincere. She
was a person of integrity who had a modest way and a lively spirit.
It was a blooming experience for her to go abroad because she was
really branching out.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Army Spec. 4 Doug Malicote, 22, and his wife, Wendy, 20, of
Lebanon, Ohio, were high school sweethearts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Om Dikshit, 54, an associate professor of earth sciences at
Central State University in Ohio, and his wife, Shanti, of Fairborn,
Ohio, were returning from their native India, where they had
attended their son's wedding. Also listed aboard the jet were the
Dikshits' daughter, Garima Rattan of Detroit, and Ms. Rattan's two
daughters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Lowenstein, 21, of Mendham, N.J., was a Syracuse
University student who studied abroad with longtime girlfriend Beth
Moritz of Highland Park, Ill. He hoped to be a clinical
psychologist. He and his girlfriend parted at London's Heathrow
Airport _ she on to Chicago, safely, he on Flight 103. He was a
member of the fraternity Zeta Psi, which lost a frat brother in 1983
in the Marine barracks bombing in Beirut.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Writer David Dornstein, 25, of Elkins Park, Pa., was returning
home from Israel, where he had begun his first novel. ``He was about
to submit the first part for publication,'' said his father, Perry
Dornstein.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Cardwell, 21, of Cresco, Pa., participated in the
Syracuse program. Cardwell's father, Anthony J. Cardwell, said his
son was a technical theater major and had been in London since Labor
Day as part of an exchange program.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Lilibeth Macalolooy, 27, a Pan Am flight attendant, grew up in
Long Beach, Calif., after emigrating to the United States from the
Philippines with her family when she was 11, her mother said. ``I
always worry about her,'' her mother sobbed Thursday. ``Before I
sleep every night I pray, `Oh, please help my daughter.' ... She had
a good life, but now no more. I can't believe that she has died.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Liz Mareck, 30, lived in Los Angeles' Venice Beach neighborhood,
where the peace activist and aspiring actress also was the lead
singer of a rock band called the Cherry Cokes. ``I just find it so
sad and tragic that somebody who spent certainly the last few years
of her life deeply dedicated to fighting for disarmament could have
possibly been killed by such a violent act,'' said Pam McCarthy, a
friend.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Flight engineer Jerry Avritt of Westminster, Calif., an off-road
bicycle enthusiast survived by a wife and two teen-age children,
mentioned fears of terrorism before leaving California for his final
flight. ``He said he felt uncomfortable about flying in Europe,
saying, ``if terrorists were going to attack, they'd do it during
the holiday season,'' neighbor Jim Gardner recalled.
</TEXT>
