<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Koreas     12-24 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koreas,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Urges Military Talks With North Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung on
Saturday urged President Roh Tae-woo to accept a North Korean call
for political and military talks on easing tension on the divided
Korean peninsula.
   Kim, who heads South Korea's largest opposition party, told
reporters that positive overtures were needed from South Korea to
end the military confrontation and expedite reunification with North
Korea.
   The leader of the Party for Peace and Democracy said substantial
progress could be made next year in talks with North Korea because
changing circumstances on the peninsula were forcing the North to
open its doors.
   North Korea has called for high-level political and military
discussions between the two Koreas that could clear the way for
summit talks on reuniting the peninsula.
   In addition, North Korea last week called for three-way talks
among North and South Korea and the United States to negotiate
durable peace measures.
   On Saturday, members of South Korea's Cabinet agreed to consider
the North's proposal for the political and military talks.
Government officials who requested anonymity said South Korea would
seek a dialogue with the North at the level of prime minister.
   The Hankook Ilbo, a leading Seoul newspaper, said contacts are
continuing through various channels to help realize Roh's desire to
hold a summit with his North Korean counterpart, Kim Il Sung.
   Both Koreas in recent months have made proposals for improving
relations, but little progress has been made. South Korean officials
have said they believe the North's recent proposals were aimed
mainly at removing U.S. troops from the South.
   North Korea contends the presence of 42,000 U.S. troops in the
South is preventing reunification of the peninsula, which was
divided in 1945 when U.S. and Soviet troops ended Japan's colonial
rule at the end of World War II.
   However, lawmakers from both sides are to resume talks on Dec. 29
on a possible non-aggression agreement and other peace measures.
   Meanwhile, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze left North
Korea Saturday after a three-day visit during which he pledged his
country would not establish diplomatic relations with South Korea,
an official report said.
   The two countries stressed in a joint communique that a reduction
of tensions between rival Koreas was ``of enormous importance in
guaranteeing peace'' in the Asia-Pacific region, the official Korean
Central News Agency said.
   The Soviet Union expressed its support for North Korean proposals
for political and military talks between North and South Korea, and
for peace talks involving the two Koreas and the United States, said
the agency dispatch, monitored in Tokyo.
   The Soviet side also reaffirmed its opposition to recognizing
both Koreas as a means of reducing tension. It pledged it would not
establish diplomatic relations with South Korea despite its
participation in the Seoul Olympic Games and its increasing trade
ties with the South.
   The United States and Japan have called on China and the Soviet
Union, North Korea's allies, to recognize South Korea in exchange
for their establishing relations with the North. But North Korea has
said such moves will lead to the permanent division of the peninsula.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
