<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SantaService     12-24 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Service,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>There's More To Being A Santa Than The `Ho, Ho, Ho!'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRETT J. BLACKLEDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roy Smoot is a shopping mall Santa Claus, but
he never says ``Ho, ho, ho,'' he never flirts, and he knows what to
do if a frightened child wets on him.
   Smoot is a graduate of the ``University of Santa Claus,'' a
nationwide how-to course sponsored by Los Angeles-based Western
Temporary Services to train a select few on the finer points of
playing the jolly old elf.
   ``I never pictured myself as a Santa Claus,'' says Smoot, who
calls himself a cowboy _ a horseshoer by trade. ``It was really
overwhelming at first.''
   This is Smoot's first experience as Santa. His towering 6-foot-4,
nearly 300-pound frame helps him play the part. But he's more than
just another pretty Santa.
   Smoot, 42, finished his training several weeks ago after being
recruited by Western to serve as one of the company's Santas.
   ``We approached him. He's got that look about him, that sparkle
in his eye,'' said Darla Lowell, manager of Western's Tulsa office.
   Western's course is based on the concept that there's more to
being Santa than wearing a red suit and laughing a loud ``Ho, ho,
ho.''
   ``You can put the facade on, but it doesn't work,'' said Jenny
Zink, national director of marketing for Western in the company's
Los Angeles office.
   Western trained more than 3,300 Santas this year to appear at
shopping malls and department stores, even restaurants and bank
lobbies, across the country.
   There's really no university, but graduates of the course do
receive a diploma from Western's ``University of Santa Claus.''
   The company has more than 325 offices that specialize in finding
temporary employees for clerical, technical, legal and accounting
services. It takes its Santa business seriously.
   ``This is a very important job,'' said Ms. Zink, who heads
Western's Santa division. ``We probably wouldn't spend half a day
training a laborer to pick up a piano.''
   Santas trained by Western must pass the company's course, which
teaches them ``how to be authentic Santas,'' Ms. Lowell said.
   There's a 40-minute introduction video, instructions on what to
say to children, suggested dialogue, lessons on how to dress like
Santa, and a requirement that each Santa know the names of all the
reindeers. The course ends with a written test that prospective
Santas must pass to graduate.
   ``Only one in 23 applicants is selected for Santa,'' Ms. Lowell
said. ``We interview a lot of people, check references and verify
they are people of high character and morals.''
   Western, which has provided Santas nationwide for 21 years,
advises its Santas to follow the guidelines it provides when dealing
with children. ``We frown upon any type of originality because it
has been proven that this brings disaster,'' reads the company's
manual for the ``Santa technique.''
   Santas should address children as ``young fellow'' or ``young
lady;'' refer to parents as ``folks'' because many children are
adopted; never flirt _ Santa is married; ask children what toys they
want for Christmas so they won't ask for intangible items, such as
the reuniting of divorced parents; never make quick, jerky movements
with small children who might be frightened by something unexpected;
and if a child wets, calmly lift the child and cheerfully hand them
back to the parent.
   Perhaps the most interesting instruction involves what most
people identify with Santa. ``We omit the ``Ho, ho, ho'' because it
may frighten the children,'' the Western training manual states.
``Talk softly.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
