<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GrateLife Bjt   12-24 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grate Life, Bjt,980</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Home For Christmas: Do Homeless Prefer The Grate?
^By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As President Reagan basks in the warmth of a
California Christmas, the homeless people he said prefer to live on
the streets gather around their flameless urban campfires in the wet
chill of the capital.
   A sparsely decorated pine tree stands propped against a street
lamp as a group of sturdy young men stamp their feet on a street
grate above the city's underground network of heat and steam pipes.
   These men are four blocks from the White House, where this week
Reagan spoke of the homeless during a television interview with
ABC's David Brinkley.
   ``Those people still prefer (being) out there on the grates or
the lawn to going into one of those shelters,'' the president said
in the interview broadcast Thursday.
   The American Civil Liberties Union called Reagan's remarks ``mean
spirited and insensitive,'' saying the number of homeless has
increased dramatically during his administration. Estimates range in
the hundreds of thousands, with more than 15,000 in the nation's
capital.
   But some of the ``grate people'' say Reagan was correct, in a
sense, about their preferences.
   ``Given the choice of one of the grates and the urine and the
lice and the maggots (in shelters), I'll take the grates,'' said
Robert Jackson, as a stiff, hot updraft warmed a small circle of men
in their 20s and 30s.
   Others said the shelters were full anyway; they'd been turned
away.
   None of them much liked what Reagan said about street people,
especially his suggestion that most are mentally retarded. The
president spoke of the release of mental patients from hospitals in
the face of civil liberties demands:
   ``They wanted freedom, but they walked out to where there was
nothing for them, and they are a large percentage of that group that
you see out there,'' Reagan said.
   Again, some of the street people think Reagan was partially
correct.
   ``It was all done with good intentions when they started
releasing people who were not a danger to others,'' said Robert
Moens, 29, who is clean, well-dressed, articulate and living over
the grates across the street from the State Department. ``But it's
more inhuman to let them stay out here and fend for themselves. Some
of them are psychotic and should be locked up.''
   Moens said the young men in his group are on the streets to avoid
the drug addicts, serious drunks, transvestites, criminals and
psychotics who they say infest some of the shelters in the city.
   The Sheriff, Go Go Joe and the others who live over the grates
make an odd family.
   A few said they have jobs but can't save enough to pay the
minimum $65 a week for flophouse rent.
   Reagan told Brinkley there are lots of jobs in Washington:
   ``How could they be out there when every week ... you'll find
from 60 to 75 full pages of help-wanted ads in the Washington
paper?'' the president asked.
   Go Go Joe, who prides himself on good personal hygiene and
professes a deep Christian faith, said he has had several
$3.35-an-hour, minimum-wage jobs.
   ``I challenge President Reagan to live on that,'' he said.
   The Sheriff, who would not give his real name, showed his photo
on a plastic Defense Department identification card and said he was
working at the Pentagon and comes home to his park benches at night.
   He showed a recent color photo of his 11-year-old daughter. He
said he sends her money every time he gets paid.
   ``I don't want pity,'' he said. ``I'm just in Washington trying
to get a foothold. This is our living room and that's our television
set.'' He pointed at a partially demolished building, a classy
apartment house, a drug store and Riverside Liquors.
   Liquor store co-owner Brian Fischer has a different view of the
grates.
   Some of the men are his friends. One once brought him to tears, a
fellow named Allen who came in so cold he couldn't fasten his jacket.
   ``When he asked me to help him zip up, I got an image of my
7-year-old kid, and I cried,'' said Fischer.
   He agreed that some have serious mental problems. When one of the
grate people lay down in the middle of E Street and started shooting
at the sky with his fingers, Fischer said he telephoned for the
police and an ambulance. Then, because it was lunchtime, he ordered
a pizza.
   The pizza arrived first, and the authorities a couple of hours
later, he said.
   And when an elderly, white-bearded derelict called Wolfman died a
few weeks ago after living on the streets for more than two decades,
he lay on a grate for three hours before anyone came to take away
the body, Fischer said.
   ``The president has a very valid point about them preferring to
live on the grates rather than in the Washington shelters,'' said
Fischer. ``But criminals in prison are treated better than these
people.''
   Another view of the homeless was offered Saturday by House
majority whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., in the Democratic Party's
weekly radio broadcast.
   ``The reality is,'' Coelho said, ``most of them are not much
different from you or me. They are the elderly, the veterans, the
physically disabled and the chronically ill. They are the drug and
alcohol dependent. They're the migrant farm workers ... But in ever
increasing numbers, America's homeless are working families with
kids.''
   Coelho said that while ``Ronald Reagan never understood this
issue'' of homelessness, Democrats were convinced his successor,
George Bush, ``will make a serious effort to deal with the tragedy
of homelessness.''
</TEXT>
