<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Harrison Ford, who has had a string of
successful films since he was discovered in ``American Graffiti'' 15
years ago, says his success comes from ``not giving up.''
   ``Most people in this business gave up and went on to other
things,'' Ford says in Sunday's edition of Parade magazine.
   ``If you simply didn't give up, you would outlast the people who
came in on the bus with you. I knew it was going to take 10 or 15
years.''
   Ford, who starred as Han Solo in the ``Star Wars'' trilogy and
plays a Wall Street deal maker in his newest film ``Working Girl,''
said those others on the bus ``were as talented as I am, or more
talented.''
   ``But I feel secure because I know how hard I've worked,'' he
added.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Santa Claus were a movie mogul, Bette Davis
would ask him to put the role of cosmetics queen Helena Rubenstein
under her tree.
   ``There is a great book on her. But I cannot sell the idea to
anybody because all the men say, `Who is interested in a woman who
made cosmetics?' A million women, that's who. And she is
fascinating,'' Miss Davis, 80, said.
   The actress was among members of the Los Angeles cultural scene
who were asked by the Los Angeles Times what they would ask for if
St. Nick was the ultimate patron who could OK a project regardless
of cost.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Loretta Lynn
joined American soldiers and their families in Frankfurt for a brief
but joyous Christmas reunion with relatives at home, made possible
by a live video hookup.
   Ms. Lynn, in West Germany for a United Services Organization
holiday tour, opened the reunions by joining U.S. Army Spec. 5
Jeffrey Lawson and his wife, Denise, as they exchanged family news
and shouts of ``Merry Christmas, Merry Christmas'' with folks back
in Brandywine, Md.
   Lawson's parents, Arthur and Shirley Johnson, and his
grandmother, Adelaide Gateway, waved happily at 1-year-old Jeffrey
Jr., whom they saw for the first time Friday.
   As the Lawsons' linkup drew to an end, Ms. Lynn warmly hugged
each member of the family, and with a hearty ``Merry Christmas and
Happy New Year'' the Lawsons left to permit other soldiers and their
relatives to speak to their kin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEAVER CREEK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, his
wife, Marilyn, and their three children are spending Christmas at
this Rocky Mountain ski resort.
   The family arrived Wednesday night for a 10-day vacation, but
locals were not terribly impressed.
   ``It's nice having Quayle, but famous people come through here
all the time,'' said Tom Evans, a bartender in the posh Inn at
Beaver Creek. ``This is a low-key place. And nobody expects Quayle's
vacation visit to create the kind of media circus you might see at
Aspen. People go to Aspen to be seen. They come here to get away and
hide out.''
   ``This is the kind of place where `important' people really
aren't that important,'' said Anthony Vino, of Anthony's
International, a fine jewelry shop.
   ``Nobody really falls over themselves over celebrities here,''
said Vino. ``Were Quayle to come into the store, I'd treat him as I
would anyone else.''
</TEXT>
