<DOCNO> AP881224-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChristmasBriefs     12-24 0892</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Briefs,0928</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shawn Pryer and Jennifer Crandon had
planned to get married next summer but they decided a Christmas
surprise for their parents would be more fun.
   So the northeast Kansas couple bypassed their church and took the
minister along as they headed out Thursday to Santa's house at the
Manhattan Town Center Mall.
   The former Miss Crandon, 23, who works at a hair salon at the
mall, wore a long white dress with train and veil. Santa wore red as
he gave her away.
   ``We just like doing stuff that's unique and fun,'' Pryer said
Friday. ``And we'd never heard of anyone doing something like this
before.''
   He said the couple planned to go home Christmas Eve and tell
their parents.
   ``It's like a Christmas present to both sets of parents,'' said
Pryer, 21, a student at Kansas State University. ``We're just going
to wait and see whether they notice (the rings).''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although chances for snow were slim in the
Indianapolis area, at least one local youngster will have a white
Christmas.
   Cara Curtis, 10, earned the honor when she won the city
Department of Parks and Recreation's first Wishing for a Winter
Wonderland essay contest.
   A dump truck pulled up in front of her family's home Friday
morning, and delivered ice shavings that had been collected at the
city's two ice rinks.
   Cara and her friends raced through the man-made snow, slipping
and sliding and making snowballs _ one of which landed squarely on
the nose of Mayor William H. Hudnut III.
   Cara's winning essay selected from 1,044 entries talked about the
magical qualities of snow.
   ``You can pretend that you are trudging through the arctic with
penguins sliding into the sparkling water when you play in the snow.
Or you can travel to an enchanted land or become an Olympic figure
skater swishing around on the glittering ice.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her home was gutted by a fire blamed on a
short in Christmas tree lights, but Diana Bojorquez said the holiday
has been salvaged by the generosity of others.
   Even as the fire burned Thursday morning, people began offering
help, Ms. Bojorquez said Friday.
   ``Maybe it's because it's the Christmas season,'' she said. ``It
started when we were standing outside watching our home burn. People
gave us clothing and my daughter a pair of shoes right there.
   A collection among city workers in this community 200 miles north
of Los Angeles produced $575 in cash, furniture and a 15-pound
Christmas turkey for Ms. Bojorquez and her 7-year-old daughter,
Adrienne.
   ``It's going to be a nice Christmas after all,'' Ms. Bojorquez
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CORDELE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some truck stops in Georgia are providing
Christmas trees, decorations and a variety of holiday treats to help
cheer up lonely drivers who cannot be with their families.
   At the Perlis Truckstop along Interstate 75 in central Georgia,
truckers will be greeted by Santa Claus and free Christmas dinners,
said general manager Leon Perlis.
   ``They're very appreciative of it,'' he added. ``Most of them are
feeling poorly because they're not at home on Christmas.''
   John Lee, restaurant shift manager at the Truckstops Of America
location in Conley, said his truck stop would provide a free buffet
meal that includes turkey, chicken, ham, stuffing, yams and pumpkin
pie.
   ``We appreciate them,'' Lee said. ``We're not a greedy outfit.
We're just trying to say `Happy Holiday.' They've got to have a
place when they're away from home.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no Santa Claus in Oregon.
   There is a Christmas Creek, Christmas Lake, Christmas Lake
Valley, Christmas Valley, Noel Creek and Mistletoe. But Santa Claus
is in Indiana.
   There are at least 88 places nationwide with Christmas in the
name, according to the Geographic Names Information System developed
by the U.S. Geological Survey and the U.S. Board on Geographic Names.
   There also are several Santa Clauses, a smattering of Noels and
an occasional Holly or Carol or Star or Holiday among the 2 million
U.S. place names.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HAMMOND, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A father is keeping alive the memory of his
dead son with acts of Christmas kindness for residents of a school
for the retarded.
   C.J. Moore, 58, collects and recycles about 10 tons of aluminum
cans a year so he can treat residents of the Hammond State School to
dinner and presents.
   C.J. Moore III, or Jay, was 16 when he died eight years ago. He
was retarded, but never stayed at the Hammond State School.
   Moore and his wife, Gloria, held their first party at the school
about 10 years ago, using money he earned by walking the highways
picking up aluminum cans and stashing bags of them in the woods
until he could bring his pickup truck around. He owned his own scrap
metal company.
   Now, diabetes keeps him from walking much, and he relies on other
people to donate cans at collection bins at grocery stores, camp
grounds and in his front yard in Hammond, 35 miles northwest of New
Orleans.
   Some 40 residents of the school receive a box of candy, a dollar
bill and other gifts adding up to $35.
   ``You might say, `Well, that ain't many,' but when you've got to
wrap 320 gifts, it is,'' Moore said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
