<2ND_LINE>AM-Santa Wheelchair,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheelchair Arrives For Mother Of Disabled Boy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spelling and grammatical errors in 4th graf are John's.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christmas came early this year for a disabled
boy who told Santa the only gift he wanted was a wheelchair for his
mom.
   A motorized wheelchair arrived Friday from Buffalo, N.Y., for
Victoria Coslett, 39. Weeks ago, it appeared that Ms. Coslett and
her 10-year-old son, John Wonggoun, would not celebrate Christmas.
   With his mother confined to their apartment and unable to
maneuver her old wheelchair outdoors to watch him play, Wonggoun
wrapped empty boxes to place under the sparsely decorated Christmas
tree, then sat down and wrote Santa.
   His letter said: ``The only gift i would like is an elecric
wheelchair for my mom. She can't walk and her hands are to weak for
the one welfair gave her 2 years ago. I would love to see her
outside without help and watch me play. Can you help me with my
wish?''
   The note made it as far as the U.S. Postal Service in Palm
Springs, where Denise Reusche, a clerk, opened the letter.
   Each year, the post office in the desert resort processes about
1,000 letters to Santa. Workers usually send a letter in return.
   But when Ms. Reusche read John's letter, she decided to contact
Fortress Scientific Co., a Buffalo wheelchair manufacturer, which
shipped the gift.
   Ms. Coslett and John were injured in a 1981 traffic crash. She
was left with ruptured spinal discs. John was partially brain
damaged and suffers recurring seizures and memory lapses. He also
has juvenile arthritis.
</TEXT>
