<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Train-BusWreck     12-24 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Train-Bus Wreck,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>46 Die, 67 Injured When Train Crashes Into Bus in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An express passenger train slammed into a bus
filled with peasants in northeast China, killing at least 46 people,
official reports said early Sunday.
   The train, bound for Beijing, was approaching a crossing in
Liaoning province on Friday night when the bus began to cross the
tracks, the Xinhua news agency said. Two rail cars overturned in the
crash, it said.
   National television said Saturday that 84 peasants were on the
bus, heading home to Inner Mongolia.
   The television report said 67 people were injured, many
critically, but the later Xinhua report put the number at 54. The
discrepancy could not immediately be resolved.
   The train began in the city of Dandong on the Chinese border with
Korea. Xinhua said the crash took place in central Liaoning near
Qinghemen, about 100 miles west of the provincial capital of
Shenyang.
   It said the engine and a second car were overturned and three
other train cars derailed.
   The TV showed the bus, mangled beyond recognition, and a row of
bodies at the scene. Neither it nor Xinhua said whether anyone on
the train was killed.
   Police are investigating the cause of the accident, the TV said.
   The collision was the fifth major train accident this year. The
most serious was a derailment in southwest China's Yunnan province
in January in which 88 people died. A train collision in Shanghai in
March killed 28 people, including 27 members of a Japanese high
school tour group.
   The minister of railways, Ding Guangen, resigned in disgrace in
early March after the first three accidents and his successor, Li
Senmao, promised to correct safety and maintenance failures blamed
for the earlier accidents.
   Trains are the main means of long-distance transport in China,
carrying about 1.2 billion passengers a year.
</TEXT>
