<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1547EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Ban     12-24 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Ban,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prague District Bans Further Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities in a district where
independent groups this month held their first legal rally in almost
20 years have called the rally anti-socialist and banned such
gatherings in the future, a newspaper said Saturday.
   The Communist party daily Rude Pravo said the ban was decided at
a meeting Thursday of officials from Prague's third district, close
to the city center, and organizers of the Dec. 10 rally marking 40
years of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
   In the peaceful hour-long rally, called by five unofficial
groups, well-known independent activists addressed a public crowd
for the first time since the end of 1968's ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   Several speeches called for peaceful changes in the current
system. At the end, a crowd of about 3,000 approved a declaration
calling for the release of all political prisoners, full religious
freedom, legalization of groups independent of the ruling Communist
party and a new constitution.
   Rude Pravo said the organizers of the Dec. 10 meeting ``were told
openly they did not adhere to the conditions under which they got
permission for the public gathering.''
   ``The content of slogans and some of the performances stepped
outside the boundaries of this covenant,'' wrote Rude Pravo
commentator Marie Boudova.
   The rally ``was aimed against Socialist order and proved the real
intention of organizers to misuse the gathering for political
provocation,'' she said.
   The decision was preceded by publication in Rude Pravo Dec. 15
and 16 of readers' letters attacking the Dec. 10 meeting.
   ``We cannot and must not let Czech Walesas infringe upon the
legal order, and what is worse, trifle with serious questions of
democracy and justice,'' wrote one reader Dec. 16, referring to
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa of Poland.
   Petr Uhl, one of the activists involved in negotiations with the
authorities before the Dec. 10 gathering, said there had been no
mention then of limits on the content of slogans or speeches at the
rally.
   ``It is false, quite false, that we the independent groups have
violated such conditions,'' he said.
   Uhl said neither of the two activists who met with authorities on
Thursday were in Prague over the Christmas weekend.
</TEXT>
