<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraplegic-Pregnancy,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paraplegic Woman Believed to Have Been Raped Delivers Healthy Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A paraplegic woman disabled by head injuries
gave birth to a healthy girl who police believe was conceived when
the woman was raped in her hospital bed. The mother was unaware she
delivered the infant, police said.
   The woman, who is in her 20s, has been hospitalized at Deaton
Medical Center since the spring of 1987. She was admitted Thursday
to University Hospital with high temperature and abdominal pains and
gave birth there.
   The woman was not able to report any rape, and police learned of
the case only when the baby was born. They were told the victim
``was not able to resist or consent to sexual advances,'' said a
police spokeswoman. So far, there is no suspect.
   ``They (Deaton officials) said she was suffering from abdominal
pains and had a disshaped abdomen. They thought she had a blockage
in the bowels,'' said the victim's sister, her legal guardian.
   At University, physicians discovered the woman was nine months
pregnant and in labor. She gave birth to a healthy 8-pound, 3-ounce
girl without realizing what had taken place, a hospital official
said.
   The sister said family members will meet to discuss moving the
woman from Deaton, where she was placed on the advice of physicians
from the University of Maryland Shock Trauma Center following her
treatment for accident injuries.
   ``I don't believe my mother or my brother will allow her to stay
there,'' said the sister, who has custody of the woman's young son
and plans to care for the newborn.
   ``I always thought Deaton patients were in protective care.
Somebody wasn't doing their job,'' she said.
   Errol G. Newport, administrator of the 320-bed facility, said
patient confidentiality prevented him from commenting on the case.
   The young woman was struck by a car in February 1987 when she ran
into traffic while trying to keep a girlfriend who had been drinking
from getting hit by a car, the sister said. The injuries left her
almost totally incapacitated and unable to talk.
   ``She can move her left leg a little and has involuntary movement
in her left hand,'' but is generally unaware of her surroundings,
the sister said.
</TEXT>
