<DOCNO> AP881224-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 1609EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-USMilitary     12-24 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Military,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>25 People Hurt In Stampede At Disco Following Tear Gas Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tear gas was fired into a crowded disco near a U.S.
Air Force base in Okinawa on Saturday, and 25 people were injured in
the stampede, two critically, police said.
   About 200 people, most of them foreigners, were in the
second-floor disco at 1 a.m. when people began rushing down the
stairs to escape the gas, said a police official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   ``The crowd panicked,'' he said.
   The official said some foreigners were among the 25 people
injured as they fell or were pushed down the stairs. The two people
in critical condition were a Japanese woman and Hong Kong Chinese
woman, he said. Both women initially were identified as Japanese.
   The two women were unconscious and were being treated at a
hospital, but were not in a life-threatening condition, police said.
The names of the injured were not immediately available.
   Police said they were investigating the incident in cooperation
with U.S. military authorities.
   The Apple House disco is in Okinawa's Uechi city near U.S. Kadena
Air Base and is frequented by foreigners, the police official said.
   Police refused to comment on whether U.S. servicemen may have
brought the tear-gas bomb into the disco. But the Japan Broadcasting
Corp. quoted an employee at the disco as saying he saw a foreigner
throw something in the room and then run out of the disco.
   The network showed pictures of the tear-gas canister it said had
been found in the disco. The tear-gas bomb is a type used by the
U.S. military, it said.
   U.S. military officials were not immediately available for
comment because of the Christmas weekend.
   In recent months, the U.S. military in Japan has been involved in
a series of incidents that have brought sharp criticism from the
Japanese press and government, and charges that it disregards public
safety.
   In October, numerous rifle bullets hit a civilian housing area
near a U.S. military firing range on Okinawa. The following month,
two U.S. Marine helicopters collided over the island, killing four
Marines.
   Also in November, a U.S. Navy skipper was transferred after his
ship fired practice shells in a commercial shipping area that came
within 330 yards of a Japanese coast guard vessel.
   About 64,000 U.S. troops are stationed in Japan under a mutual
security pact. Of the total, about 35,000 are stationed in Okinawa,
which has a population of 1.2 million.
</TEXT>
