<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite     12-24 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They sliced prices to trim hair at the Drake
Barbershop, a place some say is a real cut above.
   With a barbershop quartet harmonizing ``Easy Street'' and
champagne chilling nearby, Rick Merchant was cutting the customer's
hair for the 1920s prices of 35 cents on Christmas Eve.
   ``It's our way to commemorate the anniversary of the Drake Hotel
and the barbershop,'' Merchant said.
   His small but classy barbershop, with its mirrors trimmed with
gold paint and his barbers in white jackets and ties, is located in
the arcade under the venerable, upper-crust hotel on this city's
Magnificant Mile.
   Merchant's shop charged the rates when the barbershop and hotel
opened in 1920 _ 35 cents for a haircut, 25 cents for a manicure and
10 cents for a shoeshine.
   ``It's back to the days when a gentleman could get a haircut, a
shave, manicure _ the works for under a buck,'' said Merchant. ``I
found out the original prices from a 102-year-old man whose hair I
cut. He used to come here in the 1920s.''
   That's quite a contrast to today's Drake Barbershop, where a
haircut costs $16 and a manicure goes for $12.
</TEXT>
