<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Japan-Volcano     12-24 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Volcano,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcano In Northern Japan Erupts Saturday Night</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newly active volcano in northern Japan erupted
again Saturday night and early Sunday, forcing about 250 residents
and tourists to evacuate from nearby ski areas and hot spring
resorts, police said.
   Police officials said no casualties or damage were reported in
the eruption of 6,900-foot Mount Tokachi, about 560 miles north of
Tokyo.
   The volcano first erupted Monday for the first time in 26 years,
sending columns of smoke rising more than a mile high and pouring
mud down its slopes.
   Local town officials said the volcano remained relatively calm
until its eruptions Saturday.
   The mud flow caused by the latest eruptions was reported
subsiding Sunday morning, police said.
   However, the Asahikawa Weather Observation Station warned local
residents Sunday that the volcano could erupt again.
   In 1926, heat from Mount Tokachi's eruption melted almost all
snow on the mountain, causing mudslides that killed 144 people and
injured another 200 in two nearby villages.
   A smaller eruption in 1962 killed four people.
</TEXT>
