<2ND_LINE>AM-Governor Injured,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Dakota Gov. George Mickelson Injured In Snowmobile Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIERRE, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. George Mickelson was thrown off a
snowmobile Saturday when he dropped into a 10-foot-deep ravine, and
he was hospitalized in serious condition, officials said.
   Mickelson, 47, suffered a broken collarbone and four broken ribs
when his snowmobile dropped into a ravine and he was thrown off,
press aide Gretchen Lord Anderson said.
   ``There's a bruise on his lung, but it's not punctured. He's in
some pain and he will be,'' Anderson said.
   She said the governor's physician, Dr. Tom Huber, determined that
the injuries are not life-threatening and that Mickelson did not
suffer head injuries or lose consciousness. Although Mickelson was
listed in serious condition, his doctor expects him to improve,
Anderson said.
   The first-term Republican governor, who spent several days in the
hospital in late October for a blood clot in his right leg, was
admitted to the special care unit at St. Mary's Hospital in Pierre.
   Mickelson was snowmobiling with his son and daughter on the Fort
Pierre National Grasslands south of here when the accident happened
Saturday afternoon.
   The governor's snowmobile dropped an estimated 10 feet into the
ravine. ``The snowmobile stayed upright. The governor was thrown off
onto his shoulder and right side,'' Anderson said.
   Mickelson was wearing a helmet at the time, Anderson said,
adding, ``In fact, when they left town they had forgotten it, and
the governor said they had to go back because he wouldn't ride
without one.''
   Mickelson's daughter Amy, a college sophomore, called for an
ambulance using a radio in the governor's truck.
   Huber didn't know how long the governor would be hospitalized,
Anderson said.
</TEXT>
