<1ST_LINE>u i AM-ChristmasRdp     12-24 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Christmas Rdp,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christmas Surges Anew in Far-flung Places; Disaster Victims
Comforted</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JRL2, JRL5, BEI2, BJ1, MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF DONN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The spirit of Christmas made a comeback in Peking and Soweto,
while Pope John Paul II and Queen Elizabeth II of Britain invoked
the holiday to denounce the evil of modern times and comfort those
afflicted by recent catastrophes.
   President Reagan telephoned Christmas greetings to members of the
armed forces in distant places Saturday, talking to several selected
servicemen from Egypt to the Far East.
   In China, increasing numbers of foreign tourists and more
exposure to foreign books and television has helped foster what one
Beijing newspaper called ``Christmas fever.''
   Hotels for foreigners mounted Christmas displays and people
bought up Christmas cards imported from Hong Kong. In their latest
fad, Chinese university students raised on atheism went
church-hopping Christmas Eve, and thousands of them jammed Beijing's
main Protestant and Catholic churches Saturday night.
   In the black township of Soweto, South Africa, people prepared to
enjoy a day clouded in recent years by black activists' calls for
``Black Christmas'' boycotts to protest the white minority
government.
   This year no boycotts were announced and people bought toys, sent
Christmas cards, and filled holiday shopping bags without fear of
reprisals for breaking a boycott.
   In Vatican City at St. Peter's Basilica, the pope heralded the
birth of Christ and lamented the ``evil which still persists in
human history and even, in a sense, is becoming deeper and more
widespread.''
   In parts of the world riven by recent disasters, the holiday
supplied only a bare glimmer of hope.
   In Lockerbie, Scotland, where Pan American World Airways Flight
103 crashed Wednesday and killed all 258 board as well as others on
the ground, shops remained open and churches held Christmas Eve
services.
   Yet hearts grieved as searchers combed the countryside for more
bodies. The Rev. Patrick Keegans, whose home was destroyed in the
crash, put Christmas preparations aside Saturday to meet with
relatives of victims at a counseling center in the Roman Catholic
parish hall.
   In Soviet Armenia, where a Dec. 7 earthquake killed an estimated
55,000 people, a teacher said even the holiday season could do
little to provide solace.
   ``For us Armenians, there can be no holidays this year. No New
Year's, no Christmas,'' said Edik Kasparyan, a Leninakan teacher.
``There has been too much loss, too much death.''
   In London, Queen Elizabeth broadcast an unprecedented second
Christmas message Saturday to comfort those who suffered in the Pan
Am jet disaster, the Armenian earthquake and a recent rail crash in
south London that killed 34 people.
   She said she wanted to offer her heartfelt sympathy and prayers
to those who were injured and lost loved ones in the three disasters
which ``shocked and distressed'' the entire world.
   Elsewhere, Christmas competed with social strife.
   In the occupied West Bank town of Bethlehem, where Jesus is said
to have been born, Israeli soldiers seemed to outnumber celebrants
Saturday. A driving rain, a Palestinian general strike and heavy
Israeli security kept crowds slim. In Beirut, Lebanon, friends and
relatives of American hostages Terry Anderson and Thomas Sutherland
and British captive John McCarthy hoped the season would soften the
hearts of the kidnappers. They appealed for the release of the
hostages in Christmas letters published Saturday in Beirut
newspapers.
   Despite social turmoil, terror, and disasters both manmade and
natural, millions of children around the world felt the magic of
Christmas with an innocence many of their elders lost long, long ago.
   In a Moscow apartment on Saturday, the eyes of a 5-year-old girl
named Olga lit up when a couple dressed as Ded Moroz and
Snegurochka, Grandfather Frost and a snow maiden, walked in.
   Ded Moroz opened his sack and pulled out a huge teddy bear.
   ``It's so beautiful,'' said Olga, who was herself dressed as a
princess.
   Reagan, in his pretaped radio speech, extended special Christmas
remembrances to homeless children in America and to victims of the
earthquake in Soviet Armenia.
   ``Here in our country, there are children _ without homes,
suffering from dire diseases _ whose Christmases will be makeshift
at best,'' said the president, who is spending the holidays in Los
Angeles with wife Nancy. He praised the efforts of Toys for Tots and
other organizations to provide gifts and other assistance for such
children.
   In the United States, last-minute shoppers thronged shopping
malls and last-minute travelers had most airplanes booked solid.
   At the Ocean County Mall in Toms River, N.J., manager John
DelBene said the mall's 105 stores were packed with shoppers buying
``just one more thing.''
   People were already waiting to get in when the mall opened at 8
a.m., and by noon, the parking lot was full and cars were parked on
the grass, DelBene said.
   ``It gets more hectic every year, as merchants try to beat the
prior year's figures. The trend seems to be to wait till the end,''
DelBene said.
</TEXT>
