<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Crash-Sailor     12-24 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Sailor,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Serviceman Who Missed Flight 103 Arrives Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRONTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navy machinist's mate who missed Pan Am
Flight 103 because he could not find the airline ticket counter at
London's Heathrow Airport arrived home Saturday to the joy of his
mother.
   Robert Richardson, 20, of Ironton said he planned to be aboard
the London to New York flight, which crashed Wednesday in Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing all 258 people aboard and leaving at least 10
people on the ground missing.
   But he and a friend missed Flight 103, for which they had
reservations, because they could not find the Pan Am ticket counter
at Heathrow. They took a TWA flight that left for New York 15
minutes later, before the crash of the Boeing 747 over Scotland
about an hour into the flight.
   Richardson and his wife, Kristy, drove all night from Norfolk,
Va., and arrived in Ironton about 8 a.m. Saturday.
   For six hours Wednesday, Richardson's mother, Jackie Richardson,
tried to contact Pan Am in New York to inquire about her son. She
had telephoned her daughter-in-law, who was recovering from a
miscarriage in a Norfolk hospital, and told her that Richardson's
plane was bound from London to New York.
   ``I told her the time it was supposed to come into New York and
she started screaming that the plane had crashed,'' Jackie
Richardson said.
   Kristy Richardson said she was relieved to finally hear from her
husband.
   ``I spent six or seven hours crying and in hysterics,'' she told
the Ironton Tribune. ``Everyone told me, `Think the best, think the
best.' But it's kind of hard. He called me that night and I was just
overwhelmed. I started crying again on the phone.''
   Richardson's mother said she finally reached a Pan Am official
about 9:30 p.m. Wednesday. The official said her son's name was not
on the passenger list.
   ``But you don't know for sure until you hear that voice on the
phone,'' she said.
   At 12:30 a.m., Robert called his mother in Ironton.
   ``He said `Mom,' and we both just bawled. He said, `Mom, I was
supposed to be on that plane,''' she said.
   Richardson, who is stationed on the aircraft carrier USS John F.
Kennedy, said he learned of the crash while waiting for his luggage
at Kennedy Airport in New York.
   ``A woman came up and grabbed my arm and said, `Have you seen my
baby? Have you seen my baby?' I had to tell her no, I hadn't,'' he
said. ``It was very quiet at the airport. All you heard was crying.
Nobody was talking.''
</TEXT>
