<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Christmas 2ndLd-Writethru a0618 12-24 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Christmas, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0618,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Midnight Mass; Broadcast To Soviet Union For First
Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with color from homily at
midnight Mass, CORRECT that state-run TV, sted Vatican, reported
message broadcast to Soviet Union for first time, ADDS background on
Soviet overtures to Roman Catholicism, PICKS UP 7th pvs ```It
may...'''
^By TERRY LEONARD</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II heralded the birth of Jesus
Christ in a midnight Mass homily for Roman Catholics worldwide
Saturday, and state-run Italian television said the message was
being broadcast to the Soviet Union for the first time.
   The pope, dressed in gold and white robes and carrying a
crucifix, walked into St. Peter's Basilica moments before midnight
at the end of a long cortege of priests. At the same time, church
bells chimed all over Rome to hail the arrival of Christmas.
   The pope opened the homily in St. Peter's Basilica by quoting
from Luke 2:10-11, ``I bring you good news of great joy for to you
is born a savior.'' A text of the homily was issued in advance by
the Vatican.
   ``We hear this voice which emanates from the depths of the night
of Bethlehem. The shepherds `keeping watch over their flock by
night' were the first to hear it. For this reason, the midnight
liturgy is sometimes called `the Shepherds' Mass,'' he said.
   John Paul, speaking from the papal altar under the colossal
bronze canopy designed by Bernini, noted that people of different
languages were listening to the same message on radio and television
broadcasts of the Mass to 50 countries.
   The pope, seated on a white and gold throne in front of the
altar, spoke to a congregation that included cardinals in red
vestments, formally dressed diplomats accredited to the Vatican, and
thousands of pilgrims.
   An announcer on the state-run RAI television network, which was
feeding the Mass to other stations and networks around the world,
said the message was being broadcast to the Soviet Union for the
first time. He did not elaborate.
   The Soviet Union has shown signs of overtures to the Roman
Catholic church and its domestic faithful in recent months. Earlier
this year, officials allowed celebrations to mark the 1,000
anniversary of Russian Christendom and received a delegation from
the Vatican.
   Last year the Soviets stopped jamming the Voice of America, a
radio station operated by the U.S. government. On Nov. 29, they
stopped interfering with signals of U.S.-funded Radio Liberty.
   In his midnight Mass, the pope cautioned the faithful not to be
complacent, and to find the true meaning of Christmas in the words
``a savior is born to you.''
   ``It may seem that people have achieved a great deal, and
continue to do so, in `saving' themselves with their own resources,
so that they be self-sufficient. But they are becoming more and more
convinced that they are not self-sufficient, that all the things
that are termed `civilization, progress and development' do not
reach the roots of the evil which still persists in human history
and even, in a sense, is becoming deeper and more widespread,'' the
pope said.
   ``Meanwhile the words `a savior is born to you' continue to touch
what is permanent and real in man, what is profoundly true,'' the
pontiff said.
   On Sunday, the pope was to lead a 10:30 a.m. Christmas Day Mass
in St. Peter's, the largest church in Christendom.
   That Mass is followed by the pope's traditional Christmas Day
message ``Urbi et Orbi,'' to the city and to the world.
   Earlier Saturday, in what has become a Christmas Eve custom, the
pope met with fellow Poles for the breaking of the oplatek,
paper-thin unleavened bread similar to wafers used for Communion.
   Polish families usually begin Christmas Eve dinner by passing the
wafer around the table.
   During the meeting with his countrymen, John Paul, speaking in
Polish, severely criticized what he called ``the evil traditions of
the last decades'' in Polish politics.
</TEXT>
