<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomicideRecord     12-24 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homicide Record,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Week Left To Go In 1988, NYC's Yearlong Homicide Record Broken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least seven Christmas Eve slayings pushed the
1988 homicide total to a record with a week left in the year still
to go, officials said Saturday.
   The seven slayings reported by early evening Saturday raised the
citywide total for 1988 to 1,842, breaking the record 1981 total of
1,841, said police spokesman Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell.
   On an average day in New York City, five people are murdered.
City officials, both police and elected, have repeatedly blamed
drugs and particularly crack for the rise in violence.
   In all of 1945, the Police Department reported 291 homicides; in
August 1988 alone, there were 201. Since the crack explosion in
1985, homicides have steadily increased: 1,385 in 1985, 1,582 in
1986, and 1,672 last year.
   As of last month, Assistant Police Chief Raymond Kelly said about
42 percent of this year's slayings were drug-related.
   ``These tragic statistics reflect the mayor's concern expressed
over the past 4{ years that the federal government ought to do
something about drugs flooding across our border,'' said mayoral
spokesman Lee Jones.
   The Christmas Eve slayings included a 40-year-old man stabbed to
death in his East Village apartment; an unidentified man shot once
over the eye in drug-plagued Washington Heights; a 21-year-old man
fatally shot after a dispute in a Manhattan nightclub; and a
36-year-old woman found stabbed to death in her Brooklyn apartment.
   On Friday, shoppers at a Brooklyn department store were sent
diving for cover during a shootout between teen-agers that left one
dead and three wounded. The gunfight was ignited when one teen-ager
bumped another inside the store.
   The problem is not limited to New York; in Washington, there has
already been a record set for the most homicides ever in a year. New
York ranks 10th in killings per 100,000 people, said Kelly. The top
three are Detroit, Washington and New Orleans, he said.
</TEXT>
