<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Mexico-PrisonRiot 3rdLd-Writethru a0593 12-24 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Prison Riot, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0593,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>24 Killed In Mexico Prison Riot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with death toll at 24, breakdown of
dead, arrests of three guards and four prisoners, NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TEPIC, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police stormed a prison and crushed an
uprising by inmates who were denied Christmas pardons, but the
warden and 23 other people were killed and six were injured in the
two-day siege, officials said Saturday.
   ``There was a fierce gunfight lasting about 15 minutes before the
special forces could quell the mutiny'' on Friday night, said police
officer Sergio Anzaldo, who was on duty when the commandos attacked
the prison.
   ``It was quite violent,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Authorities have arrested four inmates and three prison guards
suspected of complicity in the uprising, a state government
spokesman said Saturday.
   One of the arrested guards, hospitalized with minor wounds, was
earlier considered one of 20 hostages rescued Friday night when
police stormed the prison's administrative offices and crushed the
uprising, said Francisco Flores, a spokesman for Nayarit state
government.
   The other two guards were not there during the uprising, but they
may have allowed inmates and two outsiders into the office area
Thursday morning, the state official said.
   Anzaldo said 130 commandos flown in from Mexico City stormed the
prison after a group of inmates had held 14 prison employees and
visiting relatives hostage for 32 hours. An earlier attempt to storm
the prison Friday was repulsed.
   The uprising began Thursday after the mutinous prisoners were
denied pardons given at Christmas to inmates with good behavior.
   Flores said a preliminary report showed the mutiny began when
about six inmates arrived at the warden's office Thursday to protest
denial of the pardons.
   Two well-dressed visitors posing as lawyers approached the
building at the same time and took out guns. Flores said they had
entered the prison without being searched.
   The hostages were held in administrative offices, and the rest of
the 1,200 inmates remained under control throughout the uprising on
the outskirts of Tepic, the Nayarit state capital, 500 miles
northwest of Mexico City.
   The death toll from the original confrontation Thursday morning
and the raids Friday night was 24: Samuel Alvarado, the 31-year-old
warden of Venustiano Carranza penitentiary; Jorge Armando Duarte,
head of the Fox commando unit; 19 prisoners and three unidentified
people presumed to be prisoners, Flores said.
   Alvarado was killed in a shootout when the inmates tried to seize
the warden's office Thursday, officials said. He was reported to
have bled to death from a leg wound.
   Authorities were still trying to determine exactly how many
inmates were ultimately involved in the uprising and how the
firearms were brought into the prison.
   Celso Humberto Delgado Ramirez, governor of the state of Nayarit,
told reporters Saturday that the immediate deployment of 200 state
police had kept hundreds of visiting relatives and officials from
being trapped by the uprising, but some relatives were among the
hostages.
   Anzaldo said Red Cross volunteers recovered the bodies after the
assault and were not immediately sure about their identities. A
prisoner provided initial identifications.
   Duarte was shot shortly before nightfall Friday, when he went
into the prison compound and tried to talk the inmates into
surrendering. ``The answer was a hail of bullets which killed him
instantly,'' a state official said.
   About two hours later, police lobbed dozens of tear gas canisters
into the penitentiary and rushed it with automatic weapons blazing.
An undetermined number of people died in the raid, which was
unsuccessful.
   About 11 p.m. Friday the commandos staged a second raid, which
killed more people and succeeded, said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   At least two people besides the prison warden and commando leader
were killed before special forces stormed the inmates, he said.
   Anzaldo said the prison's security force had been doubled and
reinforced with special police.
</TEXT>
