<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LottoFever 1stLd-Writethru a0626 12-24 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lotto Fever, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0626,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business `Booming' as Drawing for Illinois' Third-Largest Lotto
Prize Nears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Lottery officials...', with winning numbers.
No announcement of whether there is a winner expected until Sunday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lottery players had visions of dollar signs
dancing in their heads on Christmas Eve and kept machines across the
state humming late Saturday, including one spot that has become
something of a lottery shrine.
   The Liquor Rack, in the southeastern town of Robinson, has earned
its reputation as a lucky lottery outlet after selling winning
tickets four times. With an estimated $37 million grand prize on the
line Saturday, the third largest ever offered in Illinois, many
lottery players made a special pilgrimage to the store.
   The winning numbers picked Saturday evening were 8, 9, 27, 33, 43
and 54. Lottery officials said they won't announce whether anyone
matched all six numbers until Sunday. And because of the holiday,
the validation of winners, if there are any, will wait until Tuesday.
   ``They're hanging out the door,'' said Gene Wilkin, owner of The
Liquor Rack. ``We can't give the thing (machine) a break.''
   The business that sells the winning ticket receives a bonus equal
to 1 percent of the winnings. Of Wilkin's four bonuses, the last two
came only a month apart, in July and August.
   ``Everybody on the road stops to see us,'' said Wilkin. ``We had
a few people come down from Champaign (100 miles away) just to pick
up their tickets.''
   State lottery spokeswoman Kathy Rem wasn't surprised. With
average sales of 1 million tickets an hour since early Saturday
morning, she said most ticket outlets were likely very busy.
   ``We weren't sure how we'd do on Christmas Eve, but I guess the
public has answered that question,'' she said. ``Business is
booming.''
   The $37 million prize is the result of three previous weekend
drawings without any player matching all six numbers drawn from
among 54 possible. While the state lottery guarantees $5 million for
each weekend drawing and rolls that amount over, the big increases
come when there are more than the usual number of tickets sold.
   Business also was brisk at Doc's Liquor Store, the northwest
Chicago suburban shop owned by Mike Wittkowski, the one-time printer
who won the largest-ever prize of $40 million four years ago.
   ``Mike still plays, but I don't know whether he's playing this
one or not It seems like everybody else is though,'' said Dino
Pappas, Wittkowski's brother-in-law and the manager of the store.
``Sales are big. Real big.''
   The second-largest Illinois prize of $39 million was claimed Nov.
5 by former state Rep. James Soper of Cicero.
   Ms. Rem said there has also been a $35 million jackpot, but that
was shared by several winners.
 
</TEXT>
