<DOCNO> AP881224-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 2034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WishboneTree     12-24 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wishbone Tree,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Decks Tree With Wishbones Painted Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOULDER, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No bones about it, Josephine Mattson's
Christmas tree, covered from tip to trunk with 525 gold-painted
wishbones, is one of a kind.
   ``It's different,'' said Mattson, a retired occupational
therapist. ``People seem to enjoy it. They've never heard of a
wishbone tree.''
   Mattson's wishbones are no paltry poultry collection, either.
Although it includes the usual chicken and turkey bones, it also has
fragile pheasant, quail and pigeon wishbones, tiny as thimbles. One
comes from a golden eagle, she said.
   Some date back decades, including the wishbone from the eagle,
which was handed down from a friend's grandfather. The golden eagles
are now protected from hunters.
   The collection started when Mattson's father established a
poultry farm in the 1930s. Her mother kept chicken, turkey, geese
and duck wishbones from family dinners on a shelf in the family
kitchen.
   The collection took off from there, said Mattson. After a Denver
newspaper reported on the tree some 30 years ago, Mattson was
showered with wishbones from well-wishers.
   The tree is topped by a big turkey wishbone turned upside down
with a bell suspended from the prongs.
   Mattson says the turkey wishbone from this year's Christmas
dinner will hang to one side of the golden eagle wishbone, making a
wish for a happy new year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
