<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CocaineHaul     12-24 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cocaine Haul,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Operation Christmas Cola' Nets $5 Million Worth of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal drug agents seized 330 pounds of
cocaine Saturday in the latest action against Colombia's notorious
Medellin drug cartel, officials said.
   A 39-year-old Cuban national also was arrested in the raid,
dubbed ``Operation Christmas Cola,'' said Ralph Lochridge, a
spokesman for the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration. He estimated
the shipment was worth $5 million.
   ``During the holiday season, drug traffickers attempt to evade
detection from law enforcement officials by moving large quantities
of drugs based on their belief that during the Christmas season
there are fewer agents on duty to catch them,'' Lochridge said.
   ``Not so for this smuggling operation. It was definitely a white
Christmas for the feds.''
   The Cuban national, Jose Thomas Alcorta of Miami, was booked for
investigation of possession of cocaine for distribution and sale,
Lochridge said.
   He was arrested in the city of Commerce, about eight miles
southeast of downtown, after allegedly loading boxes containing the
cocaine into a refrigerated semi-tractor trailer, said Lochridge.
   The seizure was part of a continuing effort by a DEA task force,
Lochridge said. In June, the group seized 660 pounds of cocaine from
alleged members of the Medellin cartel, he said.
   An arraignment for Alcorta was not immediately set.
</TEXT>
