<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MaddoxPenalty     12-24 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Maddox Penalty,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Penalizes Maddox for Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyer Alton Maddox Jr. said Saturday he would
appeal a $1,000 fine imposed on him for filing a baseless complaint
of racism in the state's court system.
   U.S. District Judge Michael Mukasey found in July that Maddox's
complaint had no basis. In a ruling released Friday by the state, he
denied a request by Maddox, who represented controversial teen-ager
Tawana Brawley, to reconsider the fine and ordered the penalty.
   Maddox, who is black, complained in the suit that he had to apply
for permission to represent an indigent defendant while a white
lawyer received such an appointment without applying first. The
state presented evidence that the white lawyer had to apply as well,
Mukasey said.
   The judge, who noted that the state panel that disciplines
lawyers was reviewing the case, ordered Maddox to pay the state
legal costs of $1,000.
   Maddox charged Saturday that the judge also was biased against
him. He said Mukasey once was a law partner with now-U.S. Attorney
Rudolph W. Giuliani, whom Maddox said ``has absolute hatred of
myself.''
   ``The only rationale that anybody can apply to this ruling is
that this judge is obviously biased because of his relationship with
Rudy Giuliani,'' Maddox said.
   The courthouse was closed Saturday and Mukasey could not be
reached for comment.
   Ms. Brawley, who is black, touched off a nationwide controversy
after claiming she had been abducted and sexually assaulted for
several days by up to six white men, including one who flashed a
police badge.
   She and her family, however, refused to cooperate with state
investigators on the advice of Maddox, another lawyer, C. Vernon
Mason, and the Rev. Al Sharpton. A state grand jury concluded that
Ms. Brawley concocted her story.
</TEXT>
