<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0631 12-24 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0631,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volunteers Clean Birds As Oil Barge Is Repaired</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with higher numbers of dead,
injured birds; oil possibly beginning to dissipate; volunteers break
off work for the night; updates length of affected beach to three
miles sted two. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `He said...'.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OCEAN SHORES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A barge that lost 70,000 gallons of
oil off the southwestern Washington coast was towed into port
Saturday after a leak was plugged, while volunteers cleaned up
oil-coated birds left in its wake.
   ``I've heard people mutter `Merry Christmas,' but I don't think
they meant it,'' said Kirk Thomas of the Washington Conservation
Corps, one of those who looked for injured birds on the beach.
   Ron Holcomb of the state Department of Ecology said more than 300
birds were brought in Saturday for cleaning at a rescue station set
up in a church in nearby Hoquiam, but 130 were found dead or could
not be saved. Sixty birds were found dead Friday night, officials
said.
   Crews stopped working late Saturday, but planned to resume
efforts early Sunday morning, Holcomb said. There were encouraging
reports that some of the oil was dissipating in the ocean, he said.
   Holcomb said oil came ashore along a three-mile stretch of ocean
beach on the jetty at the north entrance to Grays Harbor northward
to Ocean Shores. There were reports of oil-covered birds as far
north as Moclips, 15 miles north of here, and a few from south of
the Grays Harbor entrance, said Holcomb.
   He said the birds were open-ocean birds, mostly common murres,
and came ashore only because they were stricken by the spill. There
was no telling how many birds were harmed, he said.
   The barge, loaded with 2.7 million gallons of heavy oil, began
leaking Thursday night after it was struck by the tug towing it.
Just one tank, which held 250,000 gallons, was affected, and the
spill was estimated at 70,000 gallons, officials said.
   An emergency patch could not be placed on the barge until early
Saturday because of rough seas.
   Oil seeped into Grays Harbor and up the northern part of the
inlet as the leaking barge was towed south Friday night to the mouth
of the Columbia River.
   Wildlife Department spokesman Doug Zimmer said that within Grays
Harbor, there were traces of oil at the Oyhut Wildlife Recreation
Area and heavier concentrations on Sand and Goose islands.
   The islands are used as resting spots by harbor seals, but there
was no immediate evidence any seals were harmed.
   Meanwhile, the barge arrived at Astoria, Ore., just inside the
mouth of the Columbia, about midday Saturday, said Coast Guard Lt.
Cmdr. Guy Nolan of Portland, Ore.
   The level of oil and seawater in the damaged compartment was
lowered by pumping to other compartments on the barge, and the
temporary patch in the gashed tank was strengthened, Nolan said.
   Eventually, Nolan said, the barge would be towed to Portland
where it would be drained and a permanent patch installed.
   The barge is owned by Sause Bros. Ocean Towing Inc. of Coos Bay,
Ore., which hired a company to begin cleanup operations, said Dick
Lauer, manager of bulk products for Sause.
   Sause Bros. has operated coastal barges for more than 40 years,
said Lauer. He declined to comment on whether the spill was the
worst in the company's history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
