<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Barry 2ndLd-Writethru a0617 12-24 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barry, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0617,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Denies Any Drug Interest In Hotel Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new details; no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traces of cocaine were discovered in the
Washington hotel room of a former city employee who was visited by
Mayor Marion Barry, The Washington Post reported.
   However, the newspaper, in Sunday's editions, quoted a narcotics
officer as saying the test results did not necssarily indicate that
drugs were present in the room recently.
   Barry said it was purely coincidental that he visited
acquaintance Charles Lewis at his hotel room Thursday at about the
time police were checking allegations Lewis had offered drugs to
maids in exchange for sex.
   ``I would never knowingly associate with with anybody using drugs
or dealing with drugs,'' Barry was quoted as saying through a
spokesman. ``Under no circumstances would I associate with anybody
doing this.''
   The Post also reported in Sunday's editions that Barry had
visited the hotel at least six times during the past week, including
visits during the weekend of Dec. 16-17 and twice on Wednesday.
   Barry said on Friday that he visited acquaintence Charles Lewis
at his downtown hotel room on Tuesday and Thursday. Lewis became the
focus of a police investigation following several complaints by
hotel maids that Lewis offered them drugs in exchange for sex.
   Barry released a statement to the Post on Saturday through a
spokesman saying that he ``categorically'' did not visit the hotel
on Wednesday and ``did not see'' Lewis on Dec. 16. Barry, however,
said he could not remember if he visited Lewis at the hotel on Dec.
17.
   The mayor said through the spokesman that he had met with Lewis
three times, but could not remember when the third meeting occurred.
The Post said that minutes after that conversation, the mayor's
spokesman revised his statement to say ``whatever the number of days
the mayor says he saw Lewis, there were never any drugs involved.
The fact is, he doesn't recall every time he saw Lewis.''
   Barry said through his spokesman that he did not see drugs or
paraphernalia in the room, and is not aware of whether Lewis sold or
used drugs.
   The paper said Lewis, 50, was fired from in April from a
high-ranking U.S. Virgin Islands government position after
allegations were raised bout his use of government funds in a joint
Virgin Islands-city government project.
   The public integrity branch of the city Police Department is
investigating the response of two police officers who arrived at the
hotel following the initial call reporting the alleged drug offers
on Thursday. Investigators said the officers left without
interviewing or charging Lewis.
   Barry had arrived at Lewis' hotel room at about 1 p.m. while the
officers were still at the scene, The Post said.
   The paper reported that sources said Barry has made numerous
calls to police officials to find out what they have learned in
their investigation.
   Lewis, who checked out of the Ramada Inn on Friday, apparently
without having been interviewed by police, ran up a $1,990.83 bill
at the hotel on the American Express card of Robert Storey, an aide
in Barry's policy office, the Post said.
   Police said that after Lewis checked out of the hotel, internal
affairs detectives barred the room and tested it for drugs.
   The Post said two unnamed city officials familiar with testing
procedures said the results of the drug test were positive.
</TEXT>
