<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-US 1stLd-Writethru a0642 12-24 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642 ,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Complains To UN Chief About US Allegations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to ADD Libya ready to return body of U.S. pilot,
NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi has denied U.S.
allegations his country built a chemical weapons plant and accused
Washington of escalating a hostile campaign against Libya, the
official Libyan news agency JANA reported Saturday.
   Libya's foreign ministry echoed the complaint in a letter Friday
to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, JANA said.
   The news agency also reported Saturday that Gadhafi said he would
hand over the body of a U.S. pilot killed during the 1986 air raid
on Libya ordered by President Reagan.
   The U.S. government has criticized Libya recently, saying it
built a huge chemical weapons plant, and Reagan has said military
action against the plant was under consideration. Libya says the
factory in question produces pharmaceuticals.
   Gadhafi made his comments in a letter to the chairman of the
non-aligned movement, President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, JANA
reported without saying when the letter was sent.
   He urged Mugabe to help counter the U.S. campaign that he said
``constitutes a threat to international security and peace,'' said
JANA, monitored in the Italian capital.
   The letter to Perez de Cuellar sent by the secretary of the
People's Committee for the People's Foreign Liaison Bureau, or
foreign ministry, reiterated Libya's ``unequivocal rejection of
these groundless claims and allegations,'' the news agency said.
   The letter also told the U.N. chief that Libya adheres to
international conventions and accords concerning chemical weapons
and participates ``in all efforts aimed at banning chemical
weapons,'' JANA said.
   Reagan said in an interview aired Thursday night on ABC-TV that
military action against the site has been under consideration by the
United States and its allies. But ``that's a decision that has not
been made yet,'' he said.
   The United States bombed Libya in 1986 in retaliation for a
terrorist attack on a Berlin disco that killed a U.S. serviceman and
wounded 204 other people.
   Gadhafi said the body of pilot Capt. Paul Lorence would be given
to his family ``through the pope,'' said the agency, monitored in
London and Rome.
   Lorence, 31, of San Francisco was in an F-111 that disappeared
during the April 15, 1986, raid on Tripoli and Benghazi. The other
17 U.S. Air Force bombers returned safely to their bases after
dropping about 100 tons of bombs on the two cities.
   After the 1986 raids, diplomats in Libya said Gadhafi was
demanding a ransom or concessions from the United States before
returning the airman's body.
</TEXT>
