<FILEID>AP-NR-12-24-88 2356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TankerExplosion 2ndLd-Writethru a0614 12-24 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tanker Explosion, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0614,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NTSB Crews Examine Debris From Tanker Blast; Driver, Truck Had Good
Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs w3ith quotes from NTSB officials after
preliminary study; driver, truck had good records, other detail.
Picks up 6th grafs pvs, `We'll be...'. SUBS 12th graf, `The dead..',
to DELETE now-redundant first reference to truck driver Benson.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The propane truck that blew up and burned
after hitting a retaining wall on a downtown interstate, killing
nine people, had passed an inspection just the day before, officials
said Saturday.
   National Transportation Safety Board investigators picked over
debris from Friday's crash and also checked the records of the truck
and driver, who was one of those who died in the crash. The driver
had only minor violations on his record and was thoroughly familiar
with the route, officials said late Saturday.
   Eight of the dead were killed as a result of the blast and fire
following the accident, including two people injured in their homes
who died Saturday at a hospital. A ninth person died in a separate
accident in the traffic jam that resulted from the crash,
authorities said.
   A team from the NTSB examined the crash site Saturday and tried
to recreate the accident, said NTSB member James E. Burnett.
   The initial investigation showed that the truck driven by Randall
Benson, 29, of West Memphis, Ark., got a roadside inspection
Thursday by the Arkansas Department of Transportation and found free
of defects, Burnett said.
   Benson, who worked for Wooten Transports Inc., had a good driving
record and had navigated the route of the accident many times, he
said.
   ``He was thoroughly familiar with the route and with the job he
was doing,'' Burnett said. ``Obviously, something happened. We're
not ready to say the driver lost control. It could have been
something else.''
   Benson was certified as medically fit to drive hazardous
materials and had passed a drug test a year ago, Burnett said. He
driving record was clean except for backing into an object and
hitting a car while making a right turn.
   The NTSB plans to continue the investigation but estimated the
final report is far from complete.
   NTSB experts met Saturday morning ``with the various parties or
people who have involvement in this accident and organized the
investigation,'' said board spokesman Michael Benson.
   The accident involved ``interstate trucking and hazardous
materials and that's why we're concerned about that,'' he said.
   In addition to studying the records of the trucking company,
driver and truck, investigators will examine the layout of the
interstate and the response of emergency personnel, he said.
   ``We'll be looking at probable cause and any safety issues that
may have relevance anywhere else in the country,'' Benson said.
   The 100,000-gallon tanker truck skidded on a 25 mph exit ramp of
Interstate 240 in the Midtown section of Memphis, struck a retaining
wall and exploded, said fire department Capt. Benny McDow.
   The tank shot 125 yards and crashed into a duplex apartment,
crushing the building and killing a 10-year-old girl inside. A
mammoth fireball set several other houses and nearby cars on fire.
   Benson said six NTSB investigators will head teams of local and
state authorities.
   ``The field phase of the investigation may take up to a week. The
entire investigation will take up a minimum of nine months,'' Benson
said. ``We go into it very thoroughly.''
   Some of the investigators went to the site Friday night to take a
preliminary look, and more went to the scene Saturday. The work will
continue through the Christmas holiday, said Benson.
   Besides Benson, the dead included Harrison G. Lee, 34, Brighton,
Tenn., a motorist; Robert Wardlow, 40, Memphis, a motorist; Tina
Wiles, 30, Vicksburg, Miss., a motorist; Warner Wiles, 70,
Vicksburg, Miss., Mrs. Wiles' father-in-law; and Shelanda Towles,
10, killed in her house.
   Iva J. Rubesheim, 87, who lived in the other half of the duplex
from Shelanda, and James M. Malone, 57, who lived in another burned
home, both died Saturday in the Regional Medical Center.
   Traffic backed up several miles and a second truck driver, David
Bailey, 29, of West Helena, Ark., was killed when his 18-wheeler
plowed into the rear of a car tied up in the jam, police said.
</TEXT>
