<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     12-24 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0633</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration has advised
airports worldwide to tighten security because of concern _ not yet
confirmed by investigators _ that a terrorist bomb may have caused
the Pan Am crash in Scotland.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor said Friday the alert was
prompted by the crash, the heavy Christmas travel period and ``what
obviously can be considered a heightening of world tensions''
regarding terrorist activities.
   The advisory to beef up security applies to both major U.S.
airports and airlines and foreign airports served by U.S. carriers,
he said.
   McArtor, in an interview with reporters, declined to discuss
specifically Wednesday's crash of Pan Am Flight 103, in which all
258 people aboard perished.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LENINAKAN, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for survivors of the
Armenian earthquake is over, and crews will now focus solely on
clearing away tons of concrete and debris so rebuilding can begin, a
government official said.
   No one has been found alive in the mountains of bricks,
splintered wood and steel since Thursday, when workers pulled a
woman from what used to be a building in Leninakan. She later died.
   ``We did everything to sift the ruins to save the lives of
whomever might be under them. At this time, we know that no one can
be alive,'' Vardkes Artsruny, a deputy prime minister of Armenia,
said in an interview Friday.
   ``The gigantic problem now is the cleanup,'' he said, speaking in
makeshift offices previously used as a children's center.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bickering between Nicaragua and
Honduras is threatening a summit planned for next month by Central
American leaders anxious to end the civil wars and hostilities in
the region.
   The latest stumbling block comes from the International Court of
Justice at The Hague, Netherlands. The World Court agreed this week
to hear Nicaragua's claims that Honduras has been harboring and
supporting U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, who are fighting
Nicaragua's leftist government.
   Honduran Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said Wednesday
the World Court's decision threatens the future of negotiated
settlements to the region's problems. He said the court's move is
politically charged and sets ``a judicial precedent totally
incompatible with peace negotiations.''
   In addition, President Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras has
threatened to boycott regional peace talks unless Nicaragua drops
its World Court case.
   Lopez and the foreign ministers of Nicaragua, El Salvador,
Guatemala, and Costa Rica met earlier this month in Mexico. There
they agreed that heads of state would convene in January in an
effort to breathe new life into the stalled August 1987 peace plan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack addict desperate for treatment brought
police his paraphernalia, then smashed windows at two precincts
before a judge relented and sentenced him to a drug program he calls
his ``best Christmas gift yet.''
   ``I will thank him for giving me an opportunity for starting my
life back over. He is an understanding man, one of very few,''
Alexis Vega said Friday of Bronx Criminal Court Judge John Moore.
   Vega, 34, said his life had bordered on the insane until Moore
sentenced him to 90 days in a drug treatment program. As a crack
cocaine addict, Vega lost his job as a construction worker. He
stopped paying bills. He became irresponsible and dirty. His wife of
two years, Josephine Coulter, feared for their 11-month-old son and
her two daughters, now 12 and 13.
   Last July, Miss Coulter threw him out of their home in New York
City's tough South Bronx section ``because I was doing wrong,'' he
said. ``She is a Christian and I didn't want to be around her.''
</TEXT>
